column168: During off loading of 500 gallons of Toluene from a 1000 gallon compartment, when the compartment emptied out, air pressure built up, in combination with vibration of the pump, lossening the coupler lock downs and disconnecting the hose coupling away from the truck pump reducer connection. The truck pump had a 3" to 2" reducer with the 3" connected to the pump and the 2" to the hose. A velcro strap was around the lock down ears during unloading. Toluene leaked from the truck pump and the hose for less than 1 minute. Employees in attendance of the unloading immediately turned off the pump, put absorbant material on the concrete to contain the spill and soaked up the spill. The customer removed the contaminated absorbant material.
column169: The incident has been reviewed with all company truck drivers.  The velcro straps used to hold the coupler lock down ears in place have been inspected and replaced if old and worn. When hoses are replaced will consider purchase of Boss-Lock type Couplers and investgate a better secondary secure method for the Dixon couplers than the current velcro strap.

column168: Poor loading from our Kansas terminal allowed a cylinder to rub against the pallet of cartons containing gallon cans of paint - 2 gallons per carton.  The cartons were compromised due to the weight of the cylinder and the gallon cans were crushed which contributed to a loss of 1/2 to 1 gallon of paint.  This was discovered during an un-loading process at our Albuquerque terminal.  All materials were properly cleaned up and are awaiting disposition in an over pack in our Albuquerque terminal.
column169: Poor loading was the contributing factor in this release.  Better protection of freight is an issue in this industry and better and on-going training is our objective to reduce this type of freight damage.

column168: On 05/09/06 at approximately 0800, container AMFU 845612 was discovered leaking.  The shipper -  NACA Logistics was notified.  They contracted Chemical Detection Services Florida Inc. to isolate the leak and clean the container.  A 275 gallon tote of Nalco Nalstrip 231MS was found leaking.  Aprroximately 130 gallons leaked during transport.  The leak was caused by a nail that punctured the plastic tote.  The nail was holding the bracing material together in the back of the container.  The remaining 145 gallons were pumped into another tote.  The container was cleaned and the remaining 130 gallons of Nalstrip was disposed of properly.
column169: Human error caused the package failure.  Due care should be taken when nailing bracing & blocking material to insure that packages are not punctured.

column168: Our tractor trailer transporting the containers was struck in the rear while stopped waiting for another vehicle to make a left turn. The accident occurred on a two lane highway US 331 south, 9 miles south of Defuniak Springs, Florida.  The accident was the result of another tractor trailer rear ending our vehicle causing damage to an additional four other vehicles stopped behind the turning vehicle.  Our unit was loaded with 56 drums of Sulfuric Acid secured by two e-track type load bars behind the last eight drums loaded. The load bar was bent by the force of the impact allowing three drums to fall over onto the floor of the trailer.  The responders required several hours before the rear door of the trailer could be opened. During this extened period a minor leak developed between the closure and threads of one drum resulting in a slow drip of product estimated at no more than 2 gallons.  Once the rear door of the trailer was opened, the drums were uprighted by responders and the small amount of Sulfuric Acid was collected.  All spillage was contained within the vehicle with no safety related consequences or impact to the environment.
column169: The trailer was loaded with sufficient blocking and bracing to prevent movement during transportation.  The packaging was sufficient for the material contained within. The closures were confirmed as having met the requirement according to the closure instructions.  All procedures were following by personnel packaging the material and loading the containers onto the transport unit.  It is difficult to anticipate this type of incident resulting from a tractor trailer driver not paying attention to traffic stopped on the highway and impacting our vehicle at a high rate of speed.

column168: According to the information obtained the following is known.  While loading 1, 30-gallon steel drum it was punctured by a forklift.  Approximately .5 liters of free product released at the facility.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel contained the spill and performed cleanup using gloves, absorbent pads, plastic sheet, and a recovery drum.  The cleanup materials and punctured drum was placed into a 55- gallon steel over-pack which will be held at the facility’s Dangerous Goods area pending internal disposition.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the result of a forklift puncture, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: THIS INCIDENT HAPPENED WHEN THE ENGINE OF A PROPANE BOBTAIL BACKFIRED TWICE AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO A SAFE LOCATION.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE CARGO TANK OR APPURTENENCES.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED BECAUSE A MAJOR HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MOVE IN CASE THE FIRE SPREAD TO THE CARGO TANK.

UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A 5 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS DECLARED AS A CORROSIVE LIQUID TOXIC NOS, (FORMIC ACID AND PHENOL), CLASS 8(6.1), UN2922, PG II WITH THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED.CLEAR OF SCENE: 1005.

DURING TRANSPORTATION THE DRIVER FELT THE LOAD SHIFT AND STOPPED THE VEHICLE TO   INVESTIGATE.  IMMEDIATELY UPON EXITING THE VEHICLE THE DRIVER NOTICED MATERIAL WAS   LEAKING FROM THE TAILGATE.  APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE ROAD  SURFACE AND THE REMAINDER OF THE CONTAINER LEAKED INTO THE TRUCK CONTAINMENT   SYSTEM.  ONE DRUM OF MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO BE CRACKED, ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO  LEAK OUT.  THE LOAD HAD BEEN PROPERLY SECURED.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT THE CONTAINER  WAS DEFECTIVE AND FORMED A CRACK WHICH LEAKED THE MATERIAL, WHICH, IN TURN,   LOOSENED THE SECURING SYSTEM AND CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT.  THE DRIVER ACTED TO   CONFINE THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILL TO THE TRUCK CONTAINMENT SYSTEM AND BEGAN   CLEANUP OF THE SMALL ABOUT THAT LEAKED ONTO THE ROAD.  A SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY   WAS SUMMONED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP EFFORT.

column168: An ISO tanker containing Omite Technical was staged at 4953 Virginia Ave. and was in the process of being heated up prior to delivery. At approximately 10:30 pm EST a rupture occurred presumably from excess pressure build up inside the tanker. The resulting release of the material was carried by wind currents approximatley 1600 ft north towards the Cooper River. Public safety personnel as well as US Coast Guard,  SC Dept. of Health and Env. Control and Response contractor personnel responded to the site to assess and contain the release. The root cause for the release is still under investigation at this time.

column168: Unloading line for caustic railcar had been hooked up and ready for unloading.  The air line was charged (32 psi) and the employee felt the unloading line to see if product was beginning to transfer.  After the line was checked, the employee was leaving the unloading platform when he felt something spraying him from behind.  The employee turned around to discover the unloading line had ruptured at the tank car end of the unloading hose fitting.      The employee, covered in a spray of 50% caustic, headed for the safety chemical shower station to wash off his face and neck.  When the employee saw how bad the caustic leak was and that it was continuing to spray, the employee went back into the Hot Zone to cut off the air supply to the rail car.    The chemical rated 2" line ruptured just above the railcar end of the unloading hose/fitting connection.  The failure of the hose was approximately 3" or 1/2 the circumference of the hose.    From the time the line rupture began and was then isolated, approximately three minutes passed.  An additional one minute passed with the product seeping out of the line once the air supply was shut off.    Measures were taken to prevent the caustic soaked paper lying on the ground under the railcar from blowing away.  The area was flagged off and access limited to authorized personnel only.
column169: The chemical rated hose that was in use and failed was re-evaluated and replaced with another chemical rated hose of a different brand, believed to be of better quality.  The hose connection points have been modified to relieve certain stresses on the unloading hose, thus reducing risk of premature failure.  Other modifications are being discussed to include relocation of air supply line valve for safer operation by employee and spill containment  improvements.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon unloading at the Wilson Trucking Corporation facility in Savannah, Georgia, a leak was detected.  Apparently, one cardboard carton, which contained four (4) 1-gallon plastic jugs, had been punctured with a forklift during unloading.  Southern Waste Services of Savannah, Georgia was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection, three (3) 1-gallon plastic jugs within the carton, were discovered damaged, and had released their contents.  Southern Waste Services applied absorbent pads to the free liquid, wiped down the adjacent freight, and repalletized the remainder of the shipment.  Southern Waste Services overpacked the three (3) damaged jugs, spent absorbent pads, and contaminated cardboard into two (2) 30-gallon overpack drums.  Two (2) 30-gallon overpack drums were left on site pending disposition from the shipper.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a forklift puncture during unloading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: While conducting walk around inspection of vehicle driver observed some drops coming from trailer. Driver then placed a plastic container under drip to catch any material and placed absorbent pads under container and around lacal area. Driver then notified local fire department and called ER number on manifest. Then notified company of the possible leak. The material listed on the manifest was identified and and a local response team RMCAT was notified. RMCAT personal arrived on the scene at approximately 0230 hrs. RMCAT conducted a a site health evaluation and safety meeting to address any potential hazards. A small drip was identified from the trailer. A PID was used to detect volitile vapors near the leak. The PID did pick up some vapors above 300 ppm. The trailer doors where then opened and allowed to ventilate for approx 15 minutes. RMCAT then doned full face respirators with organic vapor cartridges and polyethylene coated tyvek suits to enter the trailer. An extended reach forklift was brought on site to help unload the trailer. The drums where unloaded and rearranged until the leaking drums were found. A total of three drums were discovered leaking. The first had a loose bung and the ring was not tightened down all the way. There was a viscous material all over the sides of the drum. Therefore the drum was overpacked and relabeled. The other two, in the very front of the trailer had tight bungs, but but the ring was tightened down all the way. The drums were resealed and moved to decon the trailer floor. Extra pads were laid down for any residual materials that may weep out of the wood floor. All drums were reloaded and secured. The trailer exterior was then wiped down and the driver was released. RMCAT departed the site at approx. 1030 hrs.
column169: Shipper needs to adapt a better quality control program to ensure cargo being shipped is better prepared for transportation. After trailers are then loaded they should be reinspected by a QC supervisor and documents verified for correctness.

column168: Craig Sager was driving a different forklift than normal due to his normal forklift experiencing electrical problems.  The newer forklift 94155 has a high mast and sits differently than Craigs normal forklift.  Craig was transporting a long narrow skid (Pro 200700298) on one fork to bay beside the 55 gal. drum.  Craig thought he had enough clearence to put the skid down but punctured the drum with the free fork on the forklift.  Craig immediately secured the area and begain containment of the spill.  The drum was uprighted and the puncture was covered with shrink wrap to prevent further leakage while placing the drum in a containment container.  The containment container and order has been placed in MSP-200 Haz-Mat bay by OSandD.
column169: Recomended that Craig Sager review forklift certification and be more careful when operating moving equuipment.

column168: On 05/08/06, CSXT PCC received a call from the Sullivan County Police that people were complaining of an odor coming from a stopped CSXT train, Q64708. The Sullivan County police and fire department identified tank car WCHX 23121 as the car where the odor was coming from. CSXT informed them that it was a load of class 3, N.O.S. Flammable liquid, (Crude Sulphate Turpentine). The car was moved to Vincennes, IN., where Summit Environmental was contacted to inspect the car, and found product residue around the manway. Three of the manway bolts were tool tightened and the residue cleaned from the car. The odor was no longer detected. The car was released and sent to destination.  Cause Code: 200 NARRI: 2(5+1+0)X(2+0)= 24
column169: Talked to the shipper, Newpage Corp., in Escanaba, Michigan, and asked them to review their policy on the loading and unloading of Hazardous Material Tank cars and the proper way to tighten manway bolts

column168: On May 9, 2006, at approximately 18:00 brs., CSX Personnel were notified by personnel from the First Coast Railroad that GATX 9345, a loaded tank car of anhydrous ammonia, was leaking vapors at the interchange track in Yulee, FL. The shipper was notified and a hazmat contractor (SWS) was dispatched to the scene. Upon arrival, contractor personnel found the car leaking vapor from the pressure relief valve. Contractor personnel changed the o-ring in the valve and the leak stopped.  Cause Code: 414  NARRI = 5(5+9+0) x (2+0) = 140

column168: Driver failed to unhook his pump hose from the unloading lines at the fuel storage tanks of Rhodes Travel Center.  He started to pull away when he realized what had happened.  He had already tore the unleaded and Diesel lines loose from the storage tanks.    The unleaded lines Excess flow valve closed immediately losing almost no product.  The Diesel lines Excess flow valve did not close, so the driver immediately plugged the line with spill pads.  He then used fittings that he had in his truck to cap the line.       Booms,spill pads,and a vac truck were used to absorb the approximately 400gallons or less of product, which was all contained inside the secondary containment berm.
column169: Retraining of the driver on proper unloading procedures. Ensure that he understands that he must always check and recheck that he is completely unhooked from the storage tanks before he moves his tractor.

column168: UTLX 920116 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car. Car isolated and shipper notified.Shipper representatives, One Stop Environmental, responded and found the retainer nut on the pressure relief device operating stem stripped. The valve housing and “0” rings could not be removed, inspected or replaced. The vapor release was contained and the remaining product vapors were scrubbed off and the pressure on the car brought to zero PSI. The car was purged with air pressure to further reduce product vapor. The car was forwarded under ERA movement approval to the consignee (car owner) for further inspection and repair or replacement of the defective valve.

column168: Tractor trailer overturned off Illnois 54 highway at Bellflower curve.  Witnesses indicate heavy rain and high wind at the time of the accident.  Bellflower Fire Department and Illinois State Police responded immediately. Illinois Environmental Protection Agency arrived shortly thereafter. ICI Midwest, owner of the tractor trailer was notified at 1615 hrs, May 12, 2006. Informed that trailer rear compartment had ruptured and diesel fuel spilled. Rear compartment split at seam weld about 18-24 inches long  Bodine Environmental dispatched by ICI Midwest and arrvied on scene approxiamtely 1715 hrs. Bodine immediately set containment to keep spilled fuel from moving down through the field. ICI Midwest arrived with tractor trailer to remove residual fuel from the wrecked trailer. ICI Midwest informed upon arrival that the driver had been killed because he was ejected during the rollover. Bodine Environmental cold-drilled the wrecked trailer and approximately 2400 gallons of diesel fuel was recovered by pumping into the second ICI Midwest trailer. 5100 gallon of diesel spilled into the farm field and largely soaked into the soil.  Recovery of wreck was completed by 11 pm and roadway opened.  At 0700, May 13, 2006, Bodine Environmental and Burns & McDonnell, remediation consultant, met with ICI Midwest and outlined a remediation plan.  The ILEPA was briefed and approved the plan.  An intervention trench was completed and multiple extraction wells were sunk over the next few days to contain and remove diesel fuel from the soil.  Test bores indicate the spill spread has been stopped and the spill contained in a specified area of the soil.  Remediation and extraction efforts swill ontinue for the foreseeable future until ILEPA is satisfied the spill effects have been remedied.
column169: An operational assessment is currently underway at ICI Midwest.  Illinois State Police and Department of Transportation reports indicate tractor and trailer were sound and without defect prior to the accident.  Equipment was current for tests and inspections including satisfactory roadside DOT stops in recent months.  State Police surmise driver would have survived accident if not ejected from the cab.  They surmise he was not wearing the seatbelt. Drivers have been reminded of Illinois law regarding seatbelt use and Company policy for use.  Since the accident site has had multiple rollover accidents in recetn years, all drivers have been instructed not to use the roadway unless it is the only means to a delivery location.  Drivers have been advised to reduce speed below the 45 mph posting on the specific curve.

column168: THE HORIZON PRODUCER HAD SAILED SAN JUAN, PUERTO RICO AND WAS ABOUT 12 HOURS OUT IN ROUTE TO ELIZABETH, NEW JERSEY WHEN ON MAY 2, 2006 AT 11:45 IN THE MORNING CONTAINER FSCU632973-3 IN POSITION 020608 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AN UNKNOWN LIQUID. THE LEAK RATE WAS ABOUT A HALF GALLON EVERY HALF HOUR AND ABOUT 30 GALLONS HAD LEAKED TO THE DECK AND WAS POOLING ON THE PORT SIDE.  THE DANGEROUS CARGO MANIFEST WAS CONSULTED REVEALED NO HAZARDOUS INFORMATION ON THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION.  THE CREW STARTED EXIBITING BURNING EYES FROM THE STRONG VAPORS, AND THERE WAS NAUSEA AND SOME BREATHING PROBLEMS.  CONTACT WAS MADE NOTED AS ANOTHER CARRIER CARGO, SEA STAR, THE OTHER CARRIER, WAS CONTACTED ABOUT THE PROBLEM AND CONFIRMED THE NON HAZARDOUS CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER- BASED ON THE SHIPPERS BILLING (AQUA GULF).to Sea Star. The Captain was very concerned about the fumes from the cargo so he proceeded to wash down the non hazardous cargo from the deck of the vessel to reduce the hazard to the crew. This was communicated to the National Response Center.  Horizon’s hazmat manager contacted Aqua Gulf and Sea Star and requested a packaging list of the container contents to try and determine the type of product leaking based on the volume leaking and the packaging. It was hoped that the packaging list would contain information on any large packaging that could be the source of the leak. A couple of hours later, Aqua Gulf phoned and advised that their shipper, APA, had loaded 3 drums of hazardous cargo into the container. I asked for the detailed information to communicate with the Captain on the Horizon Producer. They said that they would provide it as soon the shipper provided it to them. I asked for the hazardous information by phone to communicate with the Captain. They provided me a Material Safety Data Sheet which listed the product as UN2902, Pesticides, Liquid, Toxic, NOS (Contains 3-propyni butyl carbamate), 6.1 PGIII, Marine Pollutant. I advised the Captain on the commodity and the health hazards of the chemical. I also phoned the manufacturer, International Specialty Products (ISP), and spoke with John Shevlin who took my information and filed case #1-13827701 for his company records. He provided additional infonnation which I shared with the Captain. I asked for a better copy of the MSDS and noted that the commodity on the new MSDS had been reclassified to 1JN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid NOS with the same technical name and showing the product as a class 9 arid a marine pollutant. I phoned the Captain and provided the revised information. The precautions on the MSDS remained the same.   Out of concern for the crew, the vessel returned to San Juan where the US Coast Guard, Environmental Quality Board, Emergency Medical Personnel and a Hazmat Clean Up Contractor were scheduled to work with the vessel when it arrived. When the ship arrived, the contaminate crew were decontaminated and sent to the hospital for X-Rays and observation. The
column169: 1.  THE PACKAGES SHOULD HAVE BEEN INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING.  THIS IS DIFFICULT TO DO WITH A DRUM BUT CAN BE DONE WITH A TWO MAN OPERATION OR A LIFT TRUCK.    2. column168: Product was nose loaded to go on to another terminal.  When loader went into trailer to begin adding freight to this load, noticed a wet area and notified his supervisor, who in turn notified trained personnel to attend to the released material.  Once contained it was discovered a nail from the skid had punctured the container allowing the entire contents to escape.
column169: Pallets with nails are the worst type of packaging for hazardous materials.  Incidental spills of this nature are way too common.    Plastic molded skids without the use of nails are the way to ship this type of material.  Realizing placing this type of standard on the industry would be costly---over time it would pay for itself in the liability of releasing materials.

column168: Driver pulled into scale house and was requested to go to the back he had a liquid coming from his trailer.  It is unknown when the release began.  It was found that most of the liquid was contained inside the trailer.  The Goodland, KS Fire Department was called to the scene by the DOT officers.  The fire department handled containing and cleaning up the released material.  We have not heard of the cost of this clean up at this time.  We have been fined by the State of KS, $150.00 for section code violations 392.9(a) and 393.100(b).  We are submitting the fine amounts.  Loaders at the originating terminal will be notified of their failure to secure this load.  It appears the drum was leaking due to a nail hole from the skid.
column169: Again, skids with nails are not the way to transport hazardous materials.  The bouncing of freight on top of the skids and the weight of the drums allow the nails to work loose and puncture freight even if the nail was not apparent at the time of loading.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While trailer was stationed at the Werner Enterprises drop yard in Nashville, Tennessee, a leak was discovered.  Hepaco, Inc. of Nashville, Tennessee was dispatched to assess the site.  Upon inspection, it was determined that the freight had loose caps, which resulted in the release of approximately 50 gallons of chromic acid solution.  The free product released inside the trailer, and traveled onto the asphalt surface, and soil adjacent to the lot.  Hepaco, Inc. applied absorbent pads, and absorbent boom to the free liquid.  Hepaco, Inc. also offloaded the trailer and repackaged the insecure freight.  Four (4) 55-gallon drums were damaged, and placed into 95-gallon overpack drums as well.  Hepaco, Inc. returned to the site to excavate the impacted soil, and pressure washed the affected lot, to prevent residual contamination.  The site was restored to preexisting condition.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Apparently, the release occurred as a result of loose caps on the freight inside the trailer.  Werner Enterprises will continue to reinforce safety guidelines in relation to proper handling and loading of freight to all personnel.

column168: AN ESSENTIALLY FULLY LOADED TANK TRUCK (6000 GAL. CAPACITY) WAS PARKED AT THE RECEIVING FACILITY IN A POSITION TO UNLOAD LIQUID WASTE INTO ONE OF THE   FACILITY'S HOLDING TANKS.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS A VALVE WAS INCORRECTLY POSITIONED, THUS ALLOWING MATERIAL FROM THE HOLDING TANK TO FLOW TO AND ENTER   THE ALREADY FULL TANK TRUCK THROUGH THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THIS FORCED APPROXIMATELY  2500 GALLONS OF THE TRUCK CONTENTS OUT THE TOP (DOME) OF THE TANKER.  THE   SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE FACILITY'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEM  IN THE UNLOADING AREA.  A CONTRACTOR WAS THEN CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.
column169: TANK TRUCK LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES SHOULD BE REVIEWED WITH ALL APPROPRIATE OPERATIONS PERSONNEL.

column168: At approximately 1815 o 05/24/06, Train 930 was in the process of switching out empties and placing loads to a spot from Allied Chemical, MP K 13.77.  The switch was made while holding on to a loaded tank, UTLX 66133, which had the dome of the car unbolted.  The cut of cars were switched out to the mainline in order to double two loads back into Allied's track.  Upon stopping on the mainline, UTLX 66133, loaded with Sodium Hydroxide Solution, had approximately 20 gallons of the solution slosh out of the top of the car and onto the mainline at two car lengths north of the Allied Chemical Switch.  David Lounds, conductor of the crew, stated that some of the solution hit his arm near his elbow; this was washed off with water immediately.  Mr. Lounds reported that he was not injured, nor did he seek medical attention.
column169: Human rror caused the dome to be left open.    The Florida East Coast Railway has implemented an inspection form that must be filled out called "Empty Sodium Hydroxide Railcar Verification Procedure".  This form has eight checks for the operator to fill in and six checks for the supervisor to complete. These changes will take effect immediately.

column168: BNSF contract switch provider reported that the consignee refused GATX 47368 to enter their facility due to this tank car leaking product. GATX 47368 was isolated on a nearby spur track with a receptacle placed under tank car to catch drips. Shipper responders reported that the slow product drip emanated from around the sump area and was trickling down the outside of the bottom outlet valve. A pin hole leak was suspected in the tank shell somewhere under the insulation. The consignee provided a suitable tank car (UTLX 641767) for product transfer. Shipper responders transferred the product in GATX 47368 into UTLX 641767 by 1400 hrs. PDT, 5/11/06 without further incident. The small amount of product captured in the 5 gallon bucket under GATX 47368 had crystallized and was taken back to the shipper’s facility for appropriate disposal. The product drip from GATX 47368 had stopped after the transfer was completed. GATX 47368 was directed back to the shipper’s facility to be cleaned and purged prior to being sent to a qualified repair facility for leak source investigation and associated repairs.
column169: Pending repair facility's analysis of root cause of package failure.

column168: FILE-06-173 DOT    SHIPPER-ACUITY BRANDS    AWB#-DFW 71010416982 GGG  ON 05/09/2006 AT 1620 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FOMR THE TYLER STATION, LOCATED AT 3815 NNE LOOP 3223, TYLER, TX 75708.  CHARLENE FORM THE TYLER STATION REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A LEAKING ACUITY SHIPMENT.  THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESOPNSE TEAM.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A 5 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM CONTAINING ZEP TEAM N CLEAN.  DUE TO A SMALL LEAK FOMR THE DRUM, 1 GALLON OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE TYLER STATION VIA TRUCK #4664.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS DELCARED AS A CORROSIVE LIQUID BASIC INORGANIC NOS, (SODIUM HYDROXIDE), CLASS 8, UN3266 WITH THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED.  CLEAR OF SCENE:  1917 EST.

At 1645 on May 23,2006 an Onyx driver pulled over just east of Pendleton, OR to check a radiator hose.  While outside the truck, he noticed a solvent odor.  During an inspection of the trailer, he discovered a leaking container.  At this time he donned the appropriate PPE for remediation.      He then entered the trailer and identified material leaking from a quick-disconnect valve on the lid of the tote.  The driver pressed the quick-disconnect valve to try and relieve any pressure from the tote.  The tote did release some pressure and when quick-disconnect valve was released, it seemed to re-seat it self properly.      The driver then cleaned up the spill, which included cleaning the trailer and tote, and digging up some gravel beneath the trailer.  The driver estimated that 1-3 gallons of solvent leaked.     All generated spill cleanup material was packaged into an appropriate DOT specification container, which was labeled and marked as required.  Also a new shipping document was generated for the new container.      The driver pulled over about every 30 minutes to look at the tote for any further spillage.  It arrived at the destination facility without any further incident.      It is believed that the quick-disconnect valve was not seated properly. Pressure build-up in the tote because of elevation change may have also been a contribution factor.
column169: After an incident investigation was performed, new procedures will be used for the quick-disconnect valves.  The quick disconnect valves will be removed from the totes and replaced with threaded plugs prior to transportation.

column168: FRTL Driver arrived at customer location to deliver 5000 gallons unleaded gasoline and 3000 gallons of low sulfur diesel, as ordered by the customer at the delivery site.  FRTL driver had the customer sign off on our "Product Integrity Form", indicating that the product would fit in their tanks.  Driver began pumping off product, but noticed the customer attendant acting suspicious, so he stood near the shut-off switch.  The fuel started to leak from the top of the tank, and the driver immediately stopped the flow of product.  Ten to twenty gallons spilled, but was contained in the containment area around the tank.  Upon further investigation, it was determined that the customer ordered the gallons for gas and diesel backwards.
column169: This incident is non-preventable for Florida Rock & Tank Lines, and the actions our driver took minimized the severity of this release.  Customer must order the correct amount of product and customer must be sure load will fit before indicating that it is safe to proceed with unloading.

column168: On 16 May 2006, at approximately 0520 hours, CSXT local switcher train B72615 derailed at milepost QN 10.8, Taunton, MA. The conductor found during his inspection of the train that 6 of the 32 cars had derailed, the 12th through 15th head cars. Four contained hazardous material, one loaded boxcar and one loaded plastic pellet covered hopper car. The Albany Division BA Dispatcher was notified of the derailment, the CSXT — PSCC- Public Safety Coordination Center was notified, and the TERP —Transportation Emergency Response Plan was enacted. Notifications to the local Emergency Response Officials were made, Taunton Police, Fire and EMS responded, and the MA-Regional HazMat Team #2 responded. 16 homes were evacuated as a precaution around the derailment site by the Incident Commander. Three CSXT HazMat Sentinels responded and worked with Local, State and Federal Officials during the re-railing process. There was NO product released from the four loaded rail cars containing UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide Solution, PROX 69965, SHPX 205744, PROX 64051 and CGTX 15911. Two rail cars had minor jacket damage, three had running gear and safety appliance defects that will be repaired, prior to disposition. The Incident Commander lifted the evacuation after all the cars were rerailed.

column168: On 05/05/2006 at 0400 EST, a spill was reported on aircraft tail N7O2AX, parking at gate B12, located at Abx Air, Inc., 145 Hunter Drive, Wilmington, Ohio 45177. Spill technicians Samuel Harner and Andrew Fries donned proper personal protective equipment and responded.  The Hotline contacted Network Control Group and Aircraft Maintenance and advised of spill. Upon arrival of the spill scene, the technicians confirmed a mercury spill.  The DHL network control group was contacted to advise confirmed mercury spill. The PNFMS (electronic pilot notification form system) was referenced and it was determined that inbound Flight 412, Tail N7O2AX, ONT to ILN contained a reportable quantity of mercury. Shipment was Awb# SOP 2932564854 ORD located in container #ONTO1. This was a 2 piece shipment containing a combined weight of 36.2 kg of mercury. This shipment was also referenced in the PNFMS for outbound Flight 797, Tail N767AX, ILN to ORD with the location of load position 3A1.  Hazmat Hotline contacted John Keane, Ramp Manager at ORD and informed him of the possible leaking mercury shipment. The Hotline contacted HMHTTC Spill Response and reported the aircraft incident at ORD, requesting response. hMHTTC advised of an ETA 2 to 3 hours.  ILN management conducted an area check of the Chicago load area in the haz sort and mercury was found. The NRC (National Response Center) was contacted to report the leaking mercury. Report # 796154 was assigned to ILN and Report # 796156 was reported to the aircraft at ORD.  Hazmat response crews worked on spill mitigation at aircraft N7O2AX (aircraft located at ILN), aircraft N767AX (aircraft located at ORD), and building 207/208/209 (hazmat sort building). Response crews were also dispatched to the SOP station (origin station) and the ONT/ONR (ramp) station to conduct a check for possible mercury contamination. No mercury was found at SOP. Mercury was found at ONT/ONR ramp. Hazmat response crew mitigated mercury contamination at ONT/ONR.  Upon arrival at the ORD ramp, response crews began clean up. The 2 piece mercury shipment was located. Upon investigation of the shipment, it was found that due to a slight gouge in the outer package and a slight gouge on one of the inner plastic bottles, Approximately 6 pounds of the mercury was lost, (4 lbs on N7O2AX, 1 lb on N767AX, and 1 lb on the ground and in the haz sort). This shipment originated out of SOP, trucking to ONT on Truck # 9027, flew into ILN from ONT on Flight 412, N7O2AX, went through the haz sort area and then reloaded onto Flight 797, N767AX, ILN to ORD. This incident was reported to the Western Pacific Region Federal Aviation Administration and the Great Lakes Region Federal Aviation Administration.  Clean up crews continued to clean and do meter readings in all affected areas until they were released. SOP station was released on 5/5 with no contamination found. ONT/ONR station was released on 5/5 upon clearance by spill response team. Building 207/208/209 was

column168: While travelling on Interstate 94 Eastbound at the Highway 59 exit ramp the tractor-tanker unit was involved in a roll-over causing damage to the tanker.  Approximately 3,257 gallons of gasoline were released from the tanker and impacted some soil and freestanding water.  Marine Pollution Control of Detroit, Michigan was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Marine Pollution Control applied absorbent material and booms to contain the free liquid on the affected surface.  Marine Pollution Control used a vacuum truck to recover approximately 4,455 gallons of water and oil mixture.  Additional remediation is still pending.  Marine Pollution Control will coordinate disposal of all waste generated as a result of the incident.

column14: Route 11 NB, Lee Hi Truck Stop
column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the Lee-Hi Truck Stop off of Route 11 North in Lexington, VA the driver discovered free product leaking from his trailer.  Haz/Mat 2000, Inc. of Staunton, Virginia was dispatched to investigate the trailer and  perform the cleanup.  Haz/Mat 2000, Inc. personnel applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the affected asphalt and inside of the trailer.  Haz/Mat 2000, Inc. investigated the trailer and found five damaged 5-gallon plastic pails.  The damage to the pails was due to the load shifting due to improper blocking and bracing.  Haz/Mat 2000, Inc. removed the leaking 5-gallon containers from the trailer and recovered the contaminated absorbent material.  The cleanup materials and five damaged pails were placed into recovery drums for disposition.  Haz/Mat 2000, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated during the cleanup.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Werner Enterprises will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel

column168: The Univar USA truck was proceeding to a delivery address, when on a road with a steep incline, the load shifted and a pallet jack, two IBC’s and a 100lb pail broke through the rear door and fell off trailer, out onto the road.  One sodium hypochlorite IBC leaked a few oz. from the bung area upon impact.  The bung was tightened by the driver and leak stopped.  The calcium hypochlorite pail lid came off upon impact with the ground/road surface and an estimated 7-9 lbs of solid pellets released to the roadway. All material was cleaned up by the response team.

column169: The carrier spoke to the loader who forked the drum on the proper operation of a forklift.

column168: Our driver was given the assignment to proceed to Sasol North America (shipper) in Braithwaite, LA to pick-up a load of ethyl acrylate.  When our driver arrived at the shipper's location, Sasol North America personnel opened the dome lid and inspected the cleanliness of the trailer that the product was to be loaded.  The person who performed this task failed to secure the dome lid after the inspection.  After the trailer was inspected, the product was loaded onto the trailer.  Plant rules forbid our drivers from climbing ontop of trailers to ensure all openings are secured.  As our driver was exiting the plant and onto the roadway he noticed that product was leaking from the run-off tube which is connected to the crash box surrounding the dome lid.  The driver then climbed on top of the trailer and saw that the dome lid was open and not secured.  The driver noticed that there was approximately 1/2 gallons of product in the crashbox area and a small amount has spilled onto the roadway.  The driver then closed and secured the dome lid.  The driver then walked back to the plant and notified the shipper.  Shipper personnel removed and disposed of the product from the crashbox and the road.  Trailer was then taken back into the plant and the exterior was cleaned and de-ordorized.
column169: Shipper has procedures in-place to ensure that all trailer openings are secured before and after loading of their products.  They are now inspecting trailers before they leave the plant.

column168: The driver loaded the trailer and brought it to the operating center. During his post trip inspection he noticed a very small leak approximately 12 drops per minute. A spill pad was put under the leak location. The product was transferred into another trailer.  The trailer that had the failure was brought to a shop for inspection and repair. It was found that the shear section of the internal valve had a small crack in it which was allowing the product to leak. The shop replaced the failed piece of equipment.
column169: The annual inspection of the trailer includes pressure testing to identify this type of problem. In this particular case the trailer had been pressure tested 5 days prior to the failure and it was not found to be leaking. The failure may have been identified through a more thorough pre-trip inspection.

column168: EVENT # 14469 SPILL-D/R SIGNED-PPE G WORN. PROD SPILLED FROM THE TOP OF THE CUST TANK CLOSE TO COMPLETION OF UNL.  ABOUT 20 GAL OF HAZ PROD SPILLED WIN A CONTAINED AREA.

Driver was heading southbound on Cty Rd 5. There is a 45 mph curve to the left. Right front tire dropped off onto the shoulder. Driver over corrected and the back end of the truck swung down into ditch and overturned. The right front of the tank ruptured but ended up on the top side as the truck came to a rest lying on the drivers side. Fuel was seeping from the crack. We righted the truck and began to pump off the fuel. The truck was leaking foe about 1 hour. After pumping off the remaining fuel, we calculated that the loss was 100 gallons into the ditch. We picked what standing fuel we could and then excavated 25 yards of soil.
column169: This packaging held up extremly well considering the truck rolled 1 complete turn. The driver was not speeding. The problem was there is about a 2 inch drop from the road to the shoulder. This is what made it difficult to get the front tire back on the roadway.

column168: WHILE SKID WAS BEING LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER, THE CORNER STRUCK ANOTHER PALLET, PUNCTURING ONE BOX AND ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO RELEASE.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE SPILLAGE SWEPT, AS INSTRUCTED.
column169: USE PRECAUTIONS WHEN HANDLING FREIGHT NEAR OTHER SKIDS.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Torn Off or Damaged
column168: EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING NOR CTY. RD 214 AND HE HIT A SERIES OF DIPS IN THE ROAD.  AFTER THE LAST BUMP IN THE ROAD, HE LOOKED IN THE MIRROR AND SAW LIQUID POURING OFF THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  HE PULLED OVER ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER TO ISOLATE THE SPILL IN A LOW AREA.  HE CONTACTED THIS SUPERVISOR TO INITIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW BEGAN CLEAN-UP WITHIN A COUPLE OF HOURS AFTER THE INCIDENT.  THE TWO 330 GAL. TOTES WERE COMPLETELY EMPTY IN A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME.  THE BUTTERFLY VALVES BROKE INTERNALLY, THUS SPILLING THE ENTIRE TANKS CONTENTS.  THE SPILL DID NOT RUN OFF AND WAS CLEANED TO STATE AND COUNTY STANDARDS BY A THIRD PARTY.
column169: WE IDENTIFIED THAT THE 2 TOTE FAILURES BOTH HAD BUTTERFLY VALVES AND NOT THE MORE RIGID BALL VALVES.  EVEN THOUGH BOTH VALVES ARE DOT APPROVED VALVES, THE BALL VALVE DESIGN HOLDS UP BETTER.  AS CORRECTIVE ACTION, WE HAVE INSTRUCTED OUR TOTE, AND VALVE SUPPLIERS TO ONLY PROVIDE US WITH TOTES THAT HAVE BALL VALVES INSTALLED.  ADDITIONALLY, WE HAVE INSTITUTED AN INSPECTION PROCESS PRIOR TO TOTE FILLING THAT WILL ENSURE THE TOTES HAVE BALL VALVES AND THEY ARE IN GOOD CONDITION.

column168: Our employee strapped the stationary hose that leads from two 30,000 bulk storage tanks to the cylinder dock to the back of a cylinder truck. column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it.  Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed.  A pull away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore they have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary action.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, the TruGreen ChemLawn vehicle was involved in an accident, which damaged the tank truck, and resulted in the release of approximately 170 gallons of liquid fertilizer, and approximately 5 gallons of diesel fuel.  The liquid fertilizer is a mixture of Barricade 4 FL Herbicide, and Riverdale Triplet Low Odor Premium Selective Herbicide, which is diluted with approximately 95-98% water.  TruGreen ChemLawn utilizes the liquid fertilizer for purposes of lawn application and treatment.  The Woodbridge Police Department, Woodbridge Fire Department, and County Hazmat Team responded to assess the site.  The County Hazmat Team applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the affected asphalt surface.  The free liquid also affected a nearby storm drain, and ran into the surface soil along the edge of the roadway.  Allstate Power-Vac, Inc. of Linden, New Jersey was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Allstate Power-Vac, Inc. recovered the spent absorbent material from the asphalt surface, and applied additional absorbent pads and absorbent boom to the remaining free liquid.  Allstate Power-Vac, Inc. proceeded to flush the impacted storm drain, and used a shovel to remove the affected surface soil along the edge of the roadway.  The spent absorbent material, absorbent pads, soil, and absorbent boom were containerized into recovery drums, to be held for disposal per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. After unloading, hissing was heard from inside the fiberboard box delivered. Upon investigation it was determined that the metal cylinder inside was damaged and the entire contents of the cylinder, 1.8 kgs, were released. The cause of the release was damage to the cylinder causing a leak in the release valve. SET Environmental, Inc. responded to investigate. Upon investigation it was determined that one cylinder was damaged and released all contents. The remaining cylinders were not affected. The affected cylinder was returned to the shipper. The remainder of the shipment was forwarded to the consignee. No injuries or exposures were reported. The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and as a result of mechanical failure, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However BAX Global, Inc. personnel will continue to reenforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon exiting the Kemiron, Inc. facility in Fontana, California, a leak was discovered coming from the Pan Western vehicle.  Apparently, the manway cover had been left open on the Pan Western vehicle, which resulted in the release of approximately 25 gallons of ferric chloride solution.  The free product was released to the asphalt surface within the parking lot, and along the roadway at entrance to the facility.  Kemiron, Inc. personnel applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid.  The San Bernardino County Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Ecology Control Industries of Montclair, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Ecology Control Industries neutralized the product within the parking lot, and along the affected roadway, per instruction from San Bernardino County Fire Department.  Ecology Control Industries also recovered a minimal amount of soil at the edge of the roadway, which had been affected.  Ecology Control Industries proceeded to pressure wash the affected area to prevent residual contamination.  One 5-gallon drum of contaminated soil was generated during the cleanup.  Disposal will be coordinated directly by Kemiron, Inc. per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to an open manway cover, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: There was not a release of propane, no damage to the propane tank and no damage to the lading retention system in this bobtail rollover accident but there was a release of 2 gallons of diesel fuel.  On the day of the accident Ferrellgas called in the incident to the DOT and we were given a number of 797646.  Also in Question #19 I had to put some sort of number in there to move forward to the next screen but again, there was no release of propane.  Our driver states that as he crested a hill  another vehicle was hugging the center line.  Our driver veered to the right and dropped down into the ditch as this road has no shoulder.  Instead of trying to correct a bobtail right away drivers are taught to stay as they are until they can stop or slow down enough to safely ease back onto the road.  Before the bobtail was able to stop a driveway came upon its path.  The bobtail was already leaning to the right and as the driver drove over the driveway it righted itself then dropped off hard on the other side of the driveway so much so that our driver could not correct the bobtail and the bobtail rolled over.
column169: Our drivers are taught that if they drop off the road they are to stay off until they can stop or slow down the bobtail enough to safely ease back onto the roadway.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Driver was completing a delivery of 19% ammonium hydroxide to the customer.  When preparing to blow the delivery lines clear, a relief valve on the air line lifted, releasing approximately 2 gallons of product.  Driver closed all the valves, limiting the released amount.  Driver contacted customer and corporate office.  Released material was contained on-site.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column14: 3 m S. of Gilmer on Hwy 271
column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: While traveling Southbound on U.S. Highway 271the driver allowed the vehicle to drift off the shoulder of the road.  The vehicle then struck a culvert that was parallel to the roadway under a private driveway.  The unit then crossed the driveway and entered the ditch, the tractor and trailer became separated and the trailer rolled to the right into a small tree and fencing (the tractor remained upright).  The Texas Department of Public Safety, the Gilmer Fire Dep't. and local E.M.T. were dispatched to the scene.    A small amount of vapor was released from the vapor piping between the internal and external valves.  The internal valve remained closed.    No remediation was required and the trailer and tractor were removed from the scene by wrecker.
column169: As part of our 12 month rollover prevention training and poster program this incident will be reviewed with all drivers in an effort to prevent similar occurences.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: WHILE UNLOADING DISCOVERED LEAKING BATTERIES. CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM DISPATCHED TO MITIGATE SPILL DUE TO AMOUNT OF ACID SPILLED. SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. SHIPPER NOTIFIED AWAITING DISPOSITION ON THE BATTERIES.
column169: LOADING TERMINAL MANAGEMENT SHOULD EMPHASIS PROPER LOADING OF HEAVY PALLETS OF BATTERIES TO PREVENT THEM FALLING OVER AND LEAKING.

column168: Vent was leaking from the drum, however, the piece to actually filter the unit was missing, allowing more than a minimal amount of liquid to pass through.  The material was over the top of the drum, starting to leak through the sides.
column169: Replace vent filter with higher quality cap.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: WHILE UNLOADING, IT WAS DISCOVERED 1 CARTON, CONTAINING 12 CANS OF AEROSOL, CANS OF SPRAY, WAS CRUSHED BY FREIGHT FALLING ON TOP OF IT.  10 OF THE 12 CANS WERE PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: FREIGHT MUST BE SAFELY SECURED AND BLOCKED IN TO PREVENT FALLING OVER.  USING AIR BAGS, MTY PALLETS, DUNNAGE AND PLYWOOD TO TIGHTENED THE LOAD TO PREVENT SHIFTING.  RETRAIN IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE WAY TO LOAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE BUNG THAT WAS LOOSE. THE RELEASE WAS ABSORBED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: ALWAYS CHECK FREIGHT FOR PROPER PACKAGING WHEN ACCEPTING A SHIPMENT.

column168: Unloading a Jevic trailer when the employee noticed liquid dripping down the sides of the drums.  The gasket appears to be aged as it has cracks in the inner ring.  Drum was set on a containment pallet until clean up.
column169: New filter and gasket for sealing drum from the outside.

column169: DRIVER SHOULD HAVE SECURED HIS LOAD BEFORE PULLING AWAY FROM THE CUSTOMERS DOCK.  DISCIPLINE SHOULD BE ISSUED.

column168: WHILE LOADING THE TRAILER THE DOCK CHECKER PUNCTURED A DRUM OF CORROSIVE WITH FORKLIFT BLADES. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND OVERPACKED INTO SALVAGE RECOVERY DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER. THE DRUM WAS MOVED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BAY PENDING DISPOSAL.
column169: THE SHIFT OPERATIONS MANAGER STOPPED ENTIRE SHIFT AND CONDUCTED A MID-SHIFT MEETING TO INFORM EMPLOYEES OF THE SERIOUSNESS OF IMMEDIATE REPORTING TO A SUPERVISOR WHEN A SPILL OCCURS AND THE POTENTIAL OF HUMAN INJURY OR FATALITIES FROM EXPOSURE TO OTHER EMPLOYEES IF LEFT UNREPORTED. THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS ISSUED A WARNING LETTER IN CONFORMANCE WITH THE UNION CONTRACT AND RETRAINED IN THE OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.

column168: WHEN DOCKMAN UNLOADED SHIPMENT FROM TRAILER, THE SHUT OFF VALVE LOOSENED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE TOTE. HMONE WAS CONTACTED AND INSTRUCTIONS PROVIDED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLAGE AND DISPOSE, AS APPROPRIATE. THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TOTE SENT TO DESTINATION.
column169: USE EXTRA CAUTION WHEN HANDLING TOTES WITH BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES.

column168: Delivery was being unloaded by Rinchem when an employee noticed dried material on the side of the tote.  The tote's gasket was examined and it appears to have several cracks and was over tightened causing the leak.  The tote was set aside on some pads until clean up.  Duration of release is unknown as the material sealed itself from leaking after drying.
column169: Use gaskets of higher quality and don't over torque the gaskets screws.

column168: DOCKMAN OPENED UP THE TRAILER. HAZMAT SHIPMENT WAS ON THE TAIL. ONE CONTAINER WAS ON IT’S SIDE ON TOP OF THE OTHER CONTAINERS IN THE SHIPMENT. THIS CONTAINER WAS LEAKING FROM THE CAP. WE UPRIGHTED THE PAIL AND MADE SURE IT WOULD NOT LEAK. WE DELIVERED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT TO DESTINATION.
column169: LOAD HAZ MAT SHIPMENT AS PER OUR CORPORATE POLICIES. WE CONTACTED THE RESPONSIBLE FACILITY AND THEY WILL COVER THIS WITH THE DOCK WORKER THAT LOADED THIS FREIGHT. THEY WILL ALSO BE COVERING THIS WITH THE SUPERVISOR IN CHARGE OF THIS AREA TO MAKE SURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN IN THE FUTURE.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of concrete cleaning acid (Muriatic acid), was being utilized at the RSC Equipment Rental facility.  Approximately 25 gallons of product remained within the drum.  Apparently, while attempting to neutralize the remaining product within the one (1) 55-gallon drum, and flush the residual through the waste water treatment system at the RSC Equipment Rental facility, an overflow occurred.  The product released to the asphalt surface beneath the drum, and traveled into the waste water treatment system.  U.S. Environmental Services of North Little Rock, Arkansas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival, U.S. Environmental Services neutralized the free product on the affected asphalt, and the remaining product within the drum.  U.S. Environmental Services also washed the affected asphalt to prevent residual contamination.  The neutralized product and water were placed into the waste water treatment system, to be handled in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  No further action is required.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, RSC Equipment Rental will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Transgas unit #1413-80 was traveling westbound on 1-90 (Massachusetts Turnpike) just east of interchange 1 1A during a rain storm when the unit was cut off by a car. The driver of the CMV, in an attempt to avoid contact, took an evasive action which resulted in the CMV rolling onto its left (DRIVER) side, sliding, and coming to rest across three westbound traffic lanes at a point just west of the interchangel 1A exit ramp.  The CMV consisted of a model year 2002 International 9400i series tractor (#1413) and a model year 1982 Process Engineering, DOT specification MC 338 double walled vacuum insulated cargo tank motor vehicle (#80). The steel outer jacket of the cargo tank motor vehicle was abraded while sliding along the pavement surface, resulting in several fissures in the jacket, a loss of vacuum and a diminution of insulation properties. This caused a slow buildup of pressure in the cargo tank. The primary cargo tank did not fail.  At the time of the incident the trailer was carrying approximately 10,000 gallons of Methane-Refrigerated Liquid at a pressure of 8 psig. The cargo tank Over The Road (“OTR”) valve was in the open position. This valve leads to a pressure regulator with a set to discharge pressure of 19 psig. Normally, the OTR valve and regulator system are connected to the vapor space of the cargo tank. However, when the cargo tank rolled onto its side, the piping system containing the OTR valve and regulator filled with liquid. Because of the loss of vacuum and diminished insulation, the pressure in the cargo tank gradually increased until the set to discharge pressure of the OTR system (19 psig) was reached, causing the regulator to operate and allowing a small stream of Methane Refrigerated Liquid to escape from the vent stack.  At approximately 1000 hours, the Transgas emergency response team arrived and closed the OTR valve system and stopped the flow. Product loss from the OTR is estimated to be less than 10 gallons of liquid which immediately vaporized into the atmosphere.  A second Transgas MC 338 cargo tank motor vehicle was brought to the scene to unload the rolled over tanker. After approximately half of the product was unloaded, the rolled over tanker was righted. Once righted, the remaining product was unloaded into the second tanker.  The damaged tractor was towed from under the damaged tanker and replaced with a second tractor. The damaged tanker was then driven to the Transgas terminal in Lowell, MA.  2006060791

column168: On May 21st at 1750 hours, the Social Circle Police contacted CSX Transportation in regards to Tank Car UTLX2O41O6 (Load - Flammable Liquid N.O.S.) releasing vapors and signs of fresh product on side of rail car. The tank car was set off at the GRWR Interchange Track earlier in the day by CSX Transportation. CHEMTREC was notified (05212006006) and the shipper, Diversified CPC was informed of the release. CSX Management contacted SWS First Response to respond and secure the container. Once on site, SWS representatives found the manway gasket misaligned resulting in the release of product / vapors. SWS repositioned the gasket and secured the manway bolts / nuts with a wrench. The response crew then pressure tested the container to ensure proper securement. After completing the test, the car was released to destination. We estimate less than one half gallon of product / vapors was released from the tank car. Cause Code: 208 NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100
column169: Ensure compliance with standard tank car securement procedures prior to releasing cars for transit.

column168: On May 19th at 1950 hours, CSX Transportation Yard Crew Y22219 reported finding Tank Car GATX81066 (Load - Isopropyl Acetate) dripping product from the bottom outlet. CHEMTREC was notified (05192006086) and the shipper, Celanese LTD was informed of the release. CSX Management isolated the rail car then contacted Hepaco Environmental to respond and secure the container. Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the 2” bottom outlet auxiliary valve’s cap hanging by the chain with the valve in the closed position and properly sealed. Hepaco representatives threaded the bottom outlet auxiliary cap back into position and used a wrench to secure the secondary closure. The car was then switched into the local CSX Transflo Facility (final destination) for off loading. The shipper, Celanese LTD was contacted and will make arrangements to have the car shopped and the valve(s) inspected after off loading. We estimate less than one half gallon of Isopropyl Acetate was released from the tank car. Cause Code: 156 NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: Ensure compliance with standard tank car securement procedures prior to releasing cars for transit.

UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 4 X 2 OZ PLASTIC BOTTLES AND 1 X 16 OZ PLASTIC BOTTLES OF RESIN SOLUTION. column168: BNSF EMPLOYEES REPORTED DUST BLOWING OFF OF ENTRAINED RAIL CARS DURING TRAIN MOVEMENT.  THE UNIT TRAIN CONSISTED OF 70 OPEN TOP GONDOLAS OF SIMILAR COMMODITY WITH 67 OF THESE TENDERED UNDER THE SAME SHIPMENT DOCUMENT.  TRAIN WAS SUBSEQUENTLY PARKED AT LYLE, WA. FOR SHIPPER INSPECTION AND CORRECTIVE ACTION.  SHIPPER CONTRACTORS APPLIED A NEW APPLICATION OF THE PROHIBITIVE BINDER WHICH WAS SPRAYED ATOP THE COMMODITY INSIDE ALL OF THESE GONDOLAS.  THIS APPLICATION WAS COMPLETED ON 5/17/06.  AFTERWARDS, THIS UNIT TRAIN WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED AND IT ARRIVED AT ITS DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER REPORTED INCIDENT.  SHIPPER INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED THAT THE CURRENT LOADING PROCESS ALLOWED FOR SOME SLOPING OF THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE GONDOLAS.  THE BINDER APPLICATION APPEARED TO WEAKEN ON THE SLOPED AREAS FROM MOVEMENT VIBRATIONS.  THE LOADING PROCESS WAS ADJUSTED TO MINIMIZE OR ELIMINATE SLOPING.  THE BINDER ADHESIVE APPLICATION WAS ALSO STRENGTHENED AND ALONG WITH THE DOUBLE SPRAYING OF THE BINDER, FUTURE RAIL SHIPMENTS WITH DUST BLOWING EVENTS SHOULD BE ELIMINATED.

column168: While stopped at a rest area the driver noticed a liquid material leaking from the floor boards of the trailer.  He immediatley called for a response crew to clean the spill.  Upon arrival to the site, the er team opened the trailer and found paint leaking from one cracked drum.  The paint had flowed the length of the trailer floor, saturating the pallets of material.  The er team applied granular sorbents to the puddle of paint on the asphalt parking lot.  This material was swept up and containerized into a 55-gallon drum.    The er team then called the Oregan State Patrol to ask for permission to move the trailer to a dock facility for cleaning.  With that authorization, the trailer was moved to a dock facility close by.  The damaged drum was removed from the trailer and placed into an 85-gallon salvage drum.  The remaining drums were removed, cleaned and repalletized for shipment.  Granular sorbents were applied to the trailer floor and the waste material was swept into two 55-gallon drums for disposal.  With the trailer cleaned, the re-palletized material was placed on the truck for continued shipment to it's final destination.  The 85 gallon salvage drum was also put back in the trailer for delivery.    From the inital spill call until all of the drums were cleaned and re-placed on the trailer, approximately 10 hours elapsed.
column169: Communication will be made with this shipper to ensure proper blocking and bracing of all drums.  Load locks and additional blocking will be suggested for these shipments.  In addition, a suggestion will be made to utilize closed top 55-gallon drums for this material.

THE DRUMS WERE SHRINK WRAPPED, BUT NOT TO THE PALLET, ALSO NO LOAD BARS OR STRAPS WERE USED BY OUR DRIVER OR THE SHIPPER.  OUR DRIVER LEFT AND WENT TO HIS NEXT PICKUP WHICH WAS ONE PALLET, THEN HEADED BACK TO THE TERMINAL YARD. HE BACKED INTO THE DOCK DOOR, OUR DOCK EMPLOYEE OPENED THE ROLL-UP DOOR OF THE TRAILER & SAW FOUR DRUMS LAYING ON THEIR SIDES.  HE NOTICED. ONE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER THAT WAS LEAKING & THE ODOR WHICH KEPT HIM FROM ENTERING THE TRAILER.  THE DOOR WAS CLOSED.  THE DENVER FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED & OUR BUILDING WAS EVACUATED, THE CLEAN-UP TOOK 3 1/2 HOURS.
column169: All of our drivers are trained on the proper procedures of handling Hazardous Materials when they are hired/leased on with our company & every year while they are employed/leased on with us.  This employee has been with our company for 13 years, has handled numerous loads of hazardous materials without incident that is why I was concerned as to how this happened. When the clean-up was completed and we were allowed back into the terminal I sat down with our driver and had him describe the pick-up and the return to the yard.  When he arrived at the shipper the load consisted of 13 pallets with four 55 gallons drums strapped to each pallet for a total of 52. He knew that there would be at least one more pick-up that he would have to make and not knowing how much room he would need he asked the shipper’s receiver if the pallets could be double stacked (I explained to him that there were two mistakes he had made at this point (1) he should have called dispatch and asked about the next pick-up and the amount lie would have been getting (2) also asked about double stacking liquid drums), the man loading the freight went into their office and asked about stacking and apparently was told yes they could be double stacked.  The pallets were not in the best of condition, some of the boards were cracked and the loader was having a hard time stacking them without leaning, after rearranging he was able to keep them relatively square. Our driver signed for the load and went to his next pick-up, upon arriving at the second stop he opened the door to load his freight and everyone of the pallets from the first stop were still stacked without having moved. At this stop the pick-up was 1 pallet, he signed for the load, closed the door and headed back to the terminal.  I explained the reasons why this load should not have been accepted, (1) liquid material is in constant motion and should never be in any position other than the floor of our trailer, (2) all Hazardous Materials will be secured so there is no movement and that other material loaded around the HM will not fall onto the HM, (3) with this particular load being put on pallets there should have been several precautions taken (a) the pallets should not have had broken/missing boards, (b) there should have been a slip sheet (cardboard) on top of the pallet before the drums were set on top, (c) the drums besides having straps should have been shrink wrapped to the pallets not just to each other this would have prevented any movement of the drums off of the pallets.  My commitment to the company and our drivers is to help them understand why load securement and the proper handling of Hazardous Materials is so vital to them, the company and the industry. Training is and will be ongoing for this and all drivers within our company to ensure theirs and the motoring publics safety.

column168: On May 12, 2006, at approximately 4:15 PM CDT a tractor trailer operated by KLLM Transport Services experienced a load shift. At approximately 5:19 pm CST, KLLM Transport Services retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental clean up operations.  Based on the information provided, a crew was dispatched from TAS Environmental Services to perform the corrective actions.    The crew from TAS arrived on-site and assessed the scope of the release.  The container that released the material was near the nose of the trailer.  The crew began corrective actions by locating the damages container.  Once found the container was cut free of the shrink wrap and plugged the puncture hole.  The hole was caused by a buckling of the container under the pressure the pallet that had been stacked on top.  Once the container was removed from the trailer it was placed into an overpack drum to be salvaged by the manufacturer.  The crew stabalized the trailer for travel by securing the load.  Due to the driver being close to the shipper, the trailer was to be returned for reloading and cleaning by the shipper.

column168: While stopped at a rest area the driver noted some liquid leaking through the floor boards of the trailer.  He immediately called for a spill response crew.  Upon arrival to the site, the ER team opened the trailer to find multiple drums overturned on their side.  The paint material was leaking through the bungs in the lids and the lids themselves.  Still some other drums appeared to be leaking due to the altitude difference from sea level to the higher altitude of Colorado.      The ER team had a forklift delivered to the site to facilitate off loading of the drums and pallets.  The ER team spread out a large sheet of visqueen and began unloading each pallet on the visqueen.  The leaking drums were inspected for damage and then cleaned of the paint material on the outside of the drum.  No drums were found to be damaged.  Each cleaned drum was re-palletized and prepared for continued shipment.  Granular absorbent was applied to the floor of the truck to absorb the paint.  The waste material was then swept up and put into drums for disposal  The truck was then reloaded and allowed to leave.    The ER team returned the following day to pressure wash the asphalt area stained by the paint.   The water was captured and drummed for disposal.
column169: A suggestion will be made to the shipper to utilize closed top 55-gallon drums to ship this material.  That will alleviate the problem of leaks through the rings if the drums should fall.  In addition, filling the drums slightly less will help with deliveries to elevated altitude locations.  If the material expands there will be room within the drum.    Also, proper blocking and bracing of loads will be reviewed with the shipper and with the carrier staff.

column168: WHEN THE TANK CAR IN QUESTION ARRIVED AT THE TOLEDO FACILITY UNLOADING DOCK, EVIDENCE OF MINOR LEAKAGE AROUND THE EDUCTOR OR SUCTION LINE CAP WAS NOTED. IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD A RESIDUAL PRESSURE OF APPROXIMATELY 12 PSI. PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAR WAS BLED OFF THROUGH THE TANK CAR VENT VALVE AND FACILITY VENT DOT SYSTEM. REDUCING THE PRESSURE TO ATMOSPHERIC MINIMIZED THE POTENTIAL FOR ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. THE TANK CAR LADING WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER AND SODA ASH USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE WASHINGS. THE EDUCTOR OR SUCTION LINE CAP WAS THEN REMOVED AND THE TANK CAR UNLOADED PER NORMAL PROCEDURES.
column169: ALL TANK CARS ARE PRESSURIZED AND LEAK TESTED, THEN BLED TO ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE, PRIOR TO SHIPMENT FROM THE WHITING FACILITY. THESE PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH THE WHITING PERSONNEL. WE ARE ALSO INVESTIGATING THE FEASIBILITY OF PERFORMING THE LEAK TEST AT HIGHER PRESSURE.

column168: Case boxes of 50% Hydrogen Peroxide were loaded in a trailer transferring product from warehouse in Binghamton, NY to warehouse in Buffalo, NY.  The case boxes were secured in the trailer through the use of load straps.  When the driver arrived at the yard in Buffalo, NY for unloading, it was discovered that the straps were secured too tightly and crushed the outer packaging (box) and damaged the inner packaging (plastic bottle).  The resulting release of product from the bottle started a reaction of the Hydrogen Peroxide with the fiberboard box.  This is in turn created a fire within the body of the trailer.      Water was used by employees to mitigate the fire and the Buffalo Fire Dept. was called in as a precaution.  The fire was contained within the trailer as was all involved product.  64 gallons of product were damaged/lost and were neutralized with soda ash for proper disposal.  Response time was approximately 1.5 hours.
column169: 1)This was the first purchase of this type of packaging from this manufacturer.  Will return to our original supplier as the packaging does not seem as durable.  2) All employees had recently been through a refresher class on Oxidizer training (May 2006) which enabled the staff to handle the emergency promptly and correctly.  3)Securement techniques have been reviewed with employees responsible for initial loading of the vehicle.

column168: On 05-17-06, The Contract Repair Shop failed to properly tighten the bolts on the flange after making piping repairs.  It was a matter of time before the flange gasket was going to fail.  After hauling 4 previous loads, flange connection had loosened to the point of gasket failure before hydraulic by-pass could activate when PTO was engaged.  2.  Hydraulic Control Lever was not in the neutral position when the PTO was engaged to unload.    Tighteness of flange bolts were not checked by Terminal Shop after trailer left Contract Repair shop. Discussed quality control process of Contract Shop with the owner.  Owner concerned waived repair costs and offered to pay for any cleanup.    Driver was attempting to unload.  When he pulled up to the unload box and set his parking brakes, he engaged the PTO from inside the cab.  Apparently the hydraulic control valve was in the unload position and as soon as the PTO was engaged the pump pressed up the header piping on the trailer and blew out a 4" flange gasket between the crude pump 4" header "T".
column169: All repairs done in any outside shop will be inspected by our company shop mechanics before the unit is allowed to return to work.    Drivers to insure hydraulic control lever in detent (neutral) position after loading/unloading.

column168: Driver was exiting I-90 at Exit 4, and merging right to enter the ramp to I91 south, when a small car pulled around in front of the tractor/van trailer from the left shoulder of the ramp, causing  the driver to make a sharper right turn than intended.  This resulted in the right rear tires of the trailer to go up and over the curb and lift off the ground. The weight of the freight started to shift causing the van trailer to roll over, pulling the tractor over. As tractor/van trailer landed on it's left side, the totes carrying the nickel powder landed on their sides and a small amount on materialspilled out in front of each tote inside the van trailer. Only one of the totes broke through the roof of the van trailer and spilled  a small amount of nickel powder on to the ground. The DEP estimated about 5-10 pound of material was released onto the ground. The tractor/van trailer landed on the grass area to the left of the entrance ramp. Weather conditions were wet. State police were on the site as driver was calling 911. Driver exited the vehicle by himself.  Towing company, fire department, and DEP were called on site. When the spilled  material was discover, a remediation company was called into excavate the material and cover the area with plastic to minimize the migration due to the wet conditions.

CONRAIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REACT WAS NOTIFIED BY CONTRAIL'S A. RICHTER, ALSO ENROUTE.      REPEATED CONTACT WITH CONSIGNEE, DUPONT, DEEPWATER, NJ AND WILMINGTON, D3E PERSONNEL; AND SHIPPER, LORD CORPORATION, SAGERTOWN, PA ("MATT", FOR MSDS SHEET, PRODUCT INFORMATION; WEIGHT OF PRODUCT ADVISED TO BE "8.5 POUNDS/GALLON"); THROUGHOUT EVENING AND INTO THE FOLLOWING DAY.    REACT ARRIVED APPROXIMATELY 6:10 PM, NOTING PRODUCT CONTINUOUSLY DRIPPING FROM "A" END OF CAR, IN AND AROUND THE SILL AREA, OUTBOARD AND ON THE #1 AXLE OF CAR.  REACT CONTAINED LEAK WITH SPILL PADS, POLY TROUGH.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY REACT AND CR'S RICHTER NOTED THE TANK CAR WAS JACKETED/ INSULATED DOT - SPECIFICATION 111A100W1, BUILT 7/97, STENCILING NOTED INTERIOR OF TANK SHELL WAS COATED "6/2005, REDP".    8:55 PM:  AFTER ATTACHING A TROUGH UP UNDER THE LEAK AREA ON THE CAR, THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED BY CR CREW TO ISOLATED TRACK IN GROUP 4 OF THE PAVONIA CLASSIFICATION YARD.  COMPATIBLE VACUUM TRUCKS FROM FREEHOLD CARTAGE, WERE ORDERED BY REACT.    11:10 PM:  1ST LOAD TRANSFER BEGAN.  11:35 PM:  1ST TRANSFER COMPLETED. APPROXIMATELY 6000 GALLONS.  TRUCK IMMEDIATELY SENT TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE'S (DUPONT, DEEPWATER, NJ) WASTE WATER TREATMENT PLANT FOR UNLOADING.    5/3/06; 12:08 AM:  2ND LOAD TRANSFER BEGAN.    12:28 AM:  2ND TRANSFER COMPLETED. AT COMPLETION OF TRANSFER, THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK WAS 'STUCK', AND NOTED TO STILL CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 12" OF SOLID SLUDGE. On Tuesday, May 23, 2006, Groendyke Trailer 4247 was being trans-loaded from Martin Trailer 7797 when liquid was sprayed out the vent of the Groendyke trailer.  The trans-loading operation was a result of a customer return involving 2 compartments of acetic acid and one compartment of acetic anhydnde/acetic acid blend. Compartment #1 & #2 contained acetic add, and the customer reported Compartment #1 had trash in the boom outlet valve when they started to unload. The customer further reported leaping bottom outlet valves on compartments #2 and #3.  The acetic acid in càmpartments #1 and #2 passed product specifications, and both compartments were unloaded into 63TK-204 without incident. Compartment #3 could lot be unloaded to a product tank since it was a blend of products manufactured in Kingsport. Because the complaint was a leaking bottom outlet valve, the plan was to repackage the product and send back to customer. Even though there was no indication of a leak on the bottom outlet valve, sending the trailer back to the original customer without any changes would not have been well received. In all likelihood, the reported leak was a mis-operation of the hydraulic pump used to open bottom outlet valves at the customer location.
column169: Corrective Action  1. Establish policy with Kingsport Logistics to not authorize return orders to Texas for material that can not be recycled to a process unit.  2. Review with customer proper operation of bottom outlet valve on multi-compartment trailers.  3. Modify/write procedure to use a pump when making transfer between similar sized containers, such as truck to truck.
