A tanker truck arrived at the facility at 10:42 and requested a load of HFSA.  At 11:10 the Operator set-up the valves for loading.  At 11:15 he reset the gallon counter inside the loading shack.  He was unable to reset the gallon counter on the outside flow meter.   The driver requested 4500 gallons.  Loading of the truck commenced at 1120 at a rate of 53 gpm.  The operator began monitoring the gallon counter.  When the gallon counter reached 3800 gallons, the Operator visually checked the level in the tanker (12"-18") remaining.  At 12:40, while monitoring the gallon counter, the Operator heard the truck "running over".  He immediately hit the "Stop button" and shut the valves.  The gallon counter was reading 4000-4100 gallons at the time the truck overflowed.    There was no problem with the tanker and a subsequent investigation indicated that the cause of the release was a malfunctioning gallon counter.  The release occured over a concrete area and was completely contained there.  The spill was cleaned up and the tanker was allowed to leave.
column169: The instrument/electric department was contacted to repair the gallon counter, all loading operators were cautioned and directed to maintain visual contact while loading HFSA trucks.

Driver picked up an empty trailer at a nearby tank wash facility and was to the shipper's location in Dalton, GA to have the trailer loaded.  After loading was completed and paperwork checked te driver left the shipper's location.  Driver drove vehicle approximately 2 miles and noticed that product was leaking down the sides of the trailer.  The driver then pulled the vehicle over to the side of the road and inspected.  Unpon inspection, the driver found that the washout cap was missing.  Fire department was called.  Spilled product had evaporated prior to the fire department arriving.  Fire department inspected the area and all was clear. Washout cap was placed on the trailer and the driver comleted the delivery without further incidents.  Company investigation revealed that the driver failed to ensure the washout caps were in place before leaving the tank wash facility and prior to leaving the shipper's location.
column169: Company has strict polices in place to ensure drivers check to ensure that all trailer openings are secured when a driver picks up a trailer and directly after the trailer is loaded.  Driver was counseled on the severity of his lack of attention to detail and future spill prevention training is scheduled for all drivers from the St. Gabriel terminal.  Drivers are initially trained in spill prevention at the company's training and development center in Kingsport, TN.  Remedial spill prevention training is also administered to drivers who are identified as having problems.  Spill prevention training is also given to drivers at least annually at their respective terminals.

column168: WE HAD TO PICK UP THE 250 GALLON TANK TO PUT IN A SMALLER TANK BECAUSE THE CUSTOMER WASN'T USING MUCH PRODUCT ANYMORE.  WE FELT IT WAS NOT SAFE TO EVACUATE THE TANK ON SITE SO WE DECIDED TO BRING IT BACK TO OUR YARD TO DO SO.  WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSPORTING THE TANK, THE TANK SHIFTED IN THE BACK OF OUR TRUCK CAUSING THE TIE DOWN STRAP TO LOOSEN.  THIS ALLOWED THE TANK TO TIP TO ONE SIDE AND WHEN IT DID SO THE VALVE HIT ONE OF THE STORAGE BOX COMPARTMENTS OF THE TRUCK RESULTING IN A CRACK IN THE VALVE.  MY SERVICEMAN IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE AUTHORITIES.  THE FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND SPRAYED WATER ON THE TANK UNTIL WE COULD GET THERE WITH A WOODEN PLUG TO STOP THE LEAK.
column169: WE DID HAVE A MEETING THE FOLLOWING WEEK TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT.  THE OBVIOUS ANSWER TO THE PROBLEM WAS TO MAKE SURE THAT WE HAVE ALL TIE DOWNS TIGHT BEFORE TRANSPORTING.  WE HAVE ALSO DISCUSSED PROVIDING THE FIRE DEPT WITH A RESPONSE KIT.  THAT WAY WE WOULD BE ABLE TO HAVE THE KIT ON SITE MUCH QUICKER DUE TO ITS REMOTE LOCATION.  WE HAVE SINCE BOUGHT ANOTHER KIT AND WILL BE GIVING IT TO THE FIRE DEPT.

column168: ACFX84613 WAS REPORTED WITH FRESH LIQUID STAINS ON ITS SIDE SHELLS WITH NO SPILLAGE IMPACTING THE GROUND.  ACFX 84613 WAS CAREFULLY ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD FOR INSPECTION.  NO ACTIVE LEAK WAS OBSERVED DRUING THIS TIME.  THE STAIN ORIGIN APPEARED SOURCING FROM THE TOP FITTING AREA.  BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER INSPECTED ACFX 84613 THE MORNING OF 5/18/06.  THE BNSF RESPONDER ALONG WITH CONTRACT RESPONDERS DETERMINED THAT THE MIDLAND PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) HAD MALFUNCTIONED.  THE PRD RETEST DATE STENCILED ON TANK'S SPECIFICATION STENCIL INDICATED THAT THE PRD WAS DUE FOR RETEST IN 2004.  THE PRODUCT OUTAGE WAS CHECKED AND APPEARED APPROPRIATE.  A NEW PRD (ACF TYPE 1118, SERIAL NUMBER PP280 TESTED 5/18/06) WAS PROCURED AND PROPERLY INSTALLED BY THE CONTRACT RESPONDERS.  THE MIDLAND PRD THAT WAS REMOVED HAD A BROKEN SPRING.  THE SPRING.  THE SPRING WAS BROKEN IN SEVERAL PLACES.  ACCUMULATED SPILLAGE AROUND THE PRD OFFICE WAS WIPED.  SPILLAGE ON THE SHELL EVAPORATED.  A FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL (FRA-0600142) WAS RECEIVED ON 6/07/06 TO TRANSPORT ACFX 84613 TO THE CONSIGNEE'S DESTINATION.

column168: THE PACKAGE FAILURE WAS THE RESULT OF POOR PALLETIZING BY THE OFFERING SHIPPER.  THE METAL 5 GALLON PAILS WERE STACK 3 HIGH AND SHRINKWRAPPED ON A WOODEN SKID.  THE METAL HANDLE OF ANOTHER PAIL WAS AGAINST THE SIDE OF THE PAIL THAT FAILED AND A SMALL HOLE WAS RUBBED IN THE SIDE WALL OF THE METAL CAN.  THIS RESULTED IN A SMALL LEAK THAT SEEPED DOWN THE PAIL AND ONTO THE PALLET BELOW AND THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DURATION OF THE LEAK WAS A 20 MILE RIDE FROM THE OFFERING SHIPPER TO THE FREIGHT TERMINAL THE LOSS WAS LESS THAN 1 PINT AND DID NOT PENETRATE THE TRAILER FLOOR.  IT WAS NOT RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT AND WAS EASILY CLEANED UP IN THE HOUSE.
column169: AN ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE FROM CONWAY FREIGHT WILL BE WORKING WITH THE OFFERING SHIPPER TO SUGGEST WAYS TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF LOSS IN THE FUTURE, SIMPLY ENSURING THAT THE HANDLES WERE NOT AGAINST OTHER PAILS.  PLACING CARDBOARD BETWEEN PAILS COULD ALSO ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF FAILURE.

ON MAY 26, 2006 AT 1:44 P.M. THERE WAS AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A SULFURIC ACID SPILL AT THE NORTH WEST ACID UNLOADING DOCK.  THE DRIVER WAS HOOKED UP AND TRYING TO UNLOAD HIS TRUCK, BUT THE DOWNSTREAM AUTOMATIC VALVE WAS CLOSED.  AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT FOUND THAT PRIOR TO THE DRIVER ARRIVING AT THE UNLOADING DOCK, THE EYE WASH STATION HAD BEEN TURNED ON, WHICH CAUSED AN INTER-LOCK TO CLOSE THE AUTOMATIC VALVE.  THIS CAUSED THE LINE TO BE PRESSURIZED AND WHEN THE DRIVER TRIED TO UNHOOK FROM THE LINE, THE PRESSURE IN THE LINE CAUSED THE ACID TO SPRAY OUT.  THE DRIVER HAD THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT ON, BUT WHILE TAKING OFF HIS ACID SUIT, SOME OF THE SULFURIC ACID GOT ON HIS RIGHT ARM.  THE DRIVER WAS RINSED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE MORENCI CLINIC FOR PRECAUTION.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND RESCUE TEAM WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 15 MINUTES OF THE CALL.  WHEN SAFETY ARRIVED THEY PLACED THE DRIVERS ARM INTO THE ICE CHEST FULL OF WATER TO SUBMERGE HIS ARM.  SAFETY, ENVIRONMENTAL AND ERRT SECURED THE SCENE.  SAFETY DID A FULL INVESTIGATION AND ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED UP THE SULFURIC ACID.
column169: A CHANGE HAS BEEN MADE TO ALL EYE WASH STATIONS AT THE ACID UNLOADING DOCKS TO ENSURE EVERYONE'S SAFETY.  THE INTER-LOCKS HAVE BEEN REMOVED BETWEEN THE SAFETY SHOWERS AND THE AUTOMATIC VALVES TO SECURE THERE WILL NOT BE A REPEAT OF THIS INCIDENT.

ON MAY 31, 2006, AT APPROXIMATELY 14:05 HOURS, CSX TRAIN Q381-30 WEST BOUND ON TRACK #1, AT MILEPOST QC 181, ALBANY DIVISION, MOHAWK SUBDIVISION, DERAILED THE 2ND THROUGH 27TH HEAD CARS OF THE CONSIST.  FOURTEEN OF THE DERAILED CARS WERE RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ALCOHOLS, N.O.S. (ETHANOL) UN1987.  NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT OCCURRED DURING THIS DERAILMENT.  THE TRIBES HILL FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED FIVE OF THE LOCAL HOMES (18 RESIDENTS) NEXT TO THE DERAILMENT SITE, DUE TO CONCERNS OF THE IMPEDING THUNDERSTORMS AND NOT HAVING MADE ASSESSMENT OF THE DAMAGED TANK CARS.  THE LOCAL HOMES WERE EVACUATED FOR FOUR HOURS.  DAMAGE ASSESSMENT OF THE RAIL CARS FOUND NO LEAKS, THEREFORE, RESIDENTS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES PER THE INCIDENT COMMANDER.  THE FOLLOWING TANKS CARS SUSTAINED DAMAGE, ALTHOUGH NO PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE PACKAGE: ADMX 29986, ADMX 30693, ADMX 29237, ADMX 29757, ADMX 30200, ADMX 30524, ADMX 29984, ADMX 29230, ADMX 30449, ADMX 30659, ADMX 30539, ADMX 29682, DIMX 300031 AND ADMX 30132.

column168: BNSF INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION IN THE RAIYWARD REVEALED FRESH PRODUCT STAIN THAT WAS EVAPORATIONG ON THE TANK SHELL OF GATX 2633.  GATX 2633 WAS CAREFULLY MOVED AND ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD AT THE REPAIR TRACT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. NO SPILLAGE IMPACTED THE GROUND.  ON 5/30/2006, A BNSF MECHANICA/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER REPORRTED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE ATOP THE A-END COMPARTMENT OF THIS 3 COMPARTMENT TANK CAR APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED PRODUCT.  SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS DETERMINED THAT THIS STANINLESS STEEL LIQUID VALVE'S HANDLE WAS NOT IN THE FULLY CLOSED POSITION AND THAT IT'S CLOSURE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  RESPONSDERS REPOSITIONED THE VALVE HANDLE, FULLY CLOSING THE VALVE, AND TOOL TIGHTENENED THE CLOSURE PLUG.  ALSO, RESPONDERS FOUND THE VAPOR VALVE CLOSURE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THIS PLUG WAS ALSO TOOL TIGHTENED BY RESPONDERS.  SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED BY 1145 HRS.CDT, 5/30/2006.  RESPONSE CONCLUDED BY 1300 HRS CDT, 5/30/2007, AFT FATX 2633 WAS RECHECKED BY THE BNSF RESPONDER WHOM REPORTED NO FURTHER LEAKAGE AND ALL SPILLAGE AROUND THE AFOREMENTIONED LEAKING VALVE HAD EVAPORATED.

column168: A BNSF TRAIN WAS STOPPED ON THE UPRR MAIN TRACK BETWEEN SIDING SWITCHES AFTER ALERTED BY A TRACKSIDE WARNING DEVICE OF A TRAIN AXLE COUNT THAT CONFLICTED WITH THE TRAIN LIST.  AFTER THE TRAIN CREW CORRECTED THE TRAIN LIST FOR A MISSING RAILCAR, THE TRAIN BEGAN MOVEMENT AND DERAILED 11 RAILCARS (INCLUDING 10 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LANDENED TANK CARS WITH NONE OF THESE COMPROMISED).  LATER, DURING THE RERAILING PROCESS, THE NORTH END OF THE TRAIN WITH NON-DERAILED CARS WAS BEING PREPARED TO BE PULLED AWAY FROM THE DERAILED EQUIPMENT WHEN THE DRAWBAR SLACK RAN OUT(DOWN GRADE) AND AN ADDITIONAL SIX RAILCARS DERAILED FROM THESE DRAWBAR MOVEMENTS.  AT THIS TIME, UTLX 803708 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPORIZING LIQUID PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.   ICE FORMED FROM THE PRODUCT AUTO REFRIGERATION PROCESS AND CLOTH WRAPS WERE PLACED AROUND THE GAUGING DEVICE ORIFICE TO STOP ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  UTLX 803708 WAS UPRIGHTED AND THE GAUGING DEVICE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE BY 0800 HRS.  PDT, 5/29/06.  AFTERWARDS, THE PRODUCT IN UTLX 803708 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANKER TRUCKS.

column168: RAIL CAR LTCX #1617 HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED FROM BUTLER, PA TO AMKO SERVICES COMPANY, A CRYOGENIC CARGO TANK MANUFACTURER, IN DOVER, OH TO INVESTIGATE THE LOSS OF VACUUM ON THIS INSULATED SINGLE-UNIT RAIL TANK CAR.  DURING THE INCOMING INSPECTION, THE O RING ON THE ANNULAR SPACE SAFETY DEVICE (A LIFT PLATE) WAS FOUND TO BE DETERIORATED, AND A VALVE ON THE EVACUATION LINE WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSELY CLOSED.  AFTER TIGHTENING THE VALVE AND LUBRICATING THE O-RING, THE ANNULAR SPACE ON THE TANK CAR WAS THE EVACUATED TO A VACUUM LEVEL OF 135 MICRONS, WHERE IT SETTLED AND STABILIZED.  FURTHER VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE RAIL CAR REVEALED THAT THE 2" PIPING PASSING THROUGH THE TRANSITION PLATES (PIPE SUPPORT PLATES) FROM THE ANNULAR SPACE TO THE OPERATING VALVES ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE RAIL TANK CAR (BOTH SIDES) SHOWED SOME DEFORMATION INDICATIVE OF THE POTENTIAL SHIFT IN THE INNER CONTAINER.  THE OUTER JACKET OF THE INSULATED TANK CAR WAS THEN CUT OPEN, AND WELD THE CONNECTING THE INNER CONTAINER SUPPORT ASSEMBLY TO THE OUTER JACKET WAS FOUND TO HAVE FAILED.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN KERNERSVILLE, NC FROM INDIANAPOLIS, IN ON TRAILER 313-1739 ON 05/17/2006. THEY STACKED OTHER FREIGHT ON TOP OF THIS SHIPMENT CAUSING ONE OF THE AEROSOL CANS TO LEAK OUT.

DURING A ROUTINE DOT TRUCK STOP, DOT OFFICER SPOTTED LEAKING LIQUID FROM ONE OF THE BINS.  WHEN HE CHECKED THE PAPERWORK THE INDICATION WAS THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A SOLID.  HE DOWNED THE TRACTOR AND CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ORANGE COUNTY HAZMAT.  ELL DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH AND ELL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED.  WHEN THE ELL RESPONSE CREW ARRIVED THE PROBLEM BIN WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND THE GATE VALVE ON THE BIN WAS TIGHTENED.  IT WAS EVIDENT TO THE RESPONDER THAT WATER HAD SEAPED INTO THE CONTAINER.  THE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED IN THE BIN TRAY WITH A SMALL AMOUNT ON THE TRAILER.  THE RESIDUE COLLECTED WAS DISPOSED OF AS A D001, D003.
column169: DRIVER HAD PERFORMED HIS VISUAL CHECKS, HOWEVER A MORE CAREFUL REVIEW OF THE VALVE AREA IS RECOMMENDED.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD ALSO ENSURE THE GATE VALVES ARE SECURE AFTER LOADING THE BINS AND ALSO AGAIN PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  (THESE BINS WER IN STORAGE WAITING FOR PICKUP FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME AND THIS COULD HAVE BEEN A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR).  THERE WAS NO PROPERTY DAMAGE AND NONE OF THE RAIN WATER RESIDUE WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND.

column168: Our driver was traveling southbound on I-75 at Exit 129. Driver vehicle 2 was airlifted from scene.  Our truck driver was a fatality at the scene.    Minor amount of product released from our trailer (flammable resin solution) plus diesel fuel.  Spill response contractor was dispatched to the scene by local FD along with local Regional Emergency Response Agency.  Response contractor was NEDT.    Spilled diesel fuel entered storm drain and had to be vacuumed from drain and roadside.    Highway was closed for over several hours due to fatality at the scene and investigation.  Contractor had to hand off-load trailer and stage for shipment back to our facility in Cincinnati, OH.

column168: E. I. Dupont  Deepwater N.J.  Robyn Younger  5-8-2006     On May 5, 2006 at approximately 6:30 AM, a scheduled delivery of Anhydrous Ammonia was made to the E.I. Dupont facility in Deepwater N.J via Airgas tractor T-27 and trailer N-27. Before the start of the unloading process an ammonia leak was detected at the flange where the feed tube enters the unloading pump on the trailer. I was notified by our driver (Keith McFarland), of the situation and that the unloading process would not continue pending further investigation by Dupont engineer Robert Oldach. After a discussion between McFarland, Oldach and myself, it was determined that the leak was small and mechanical conditions were sound. It was determined that the transfer into the storage tank would proceed. The transfer took place without incident. After the transfer was completed, Dupont operators drew a vacuum on the pump and associated piping causing the remaining ammonia residue to be evacuated. This action allowed the driver to return to the Airgas facility in Palmerton, Pa. without traveling public roads with a leaking trailer. Upon arrival in Palmerton the area of the suspected leak was disassembled. The cause of the leak was found to be a rubber O-ring at the mating flange of the pump and feed tube. Repairs were made by polishing the mating surfaces of the flange and pump and  a new O-ring. The vessel, pump and associated piping were pressure tested and no remaining leaks were found.     Please do not hesitate to contact me if any further assistance is necessary.      Sincerely,.     Gene Yanick

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Mr.Hoskins was transporting wet batteries for Exide from the Bristol,TN facility to Ford Motor Company in Avon Lake, OH.  The batteries at the time of shipping and during transport were properly packaged on shrink wrapped skids and braced with wooden 2x4 from the factory.  Mr. Hoskins was traveling approximately 60 mph on the northbound side of Interstate 77 at mile marker 74 when the rear tandems separated from the trailer.  The separation of the rear tandems caused both the tractor and trailer to roll over on the right side.    The trailer was Great Dane trailer that had been manufactured in 1998.  After the accident it was discovered that Great Dane had a recall in 1999 for trailers that were manufactured in 1998 for the problem that caused the above described accident.  The recall was stated as follows: "Certain commercial van trailers with slide suspensions could have improper welds attaching the upper bogie rails to the trailer crossmembers.  Loose upper bogie rails can result in the rollover of the trailer or a vehicle crash."  We are not the original owners of this trailer therefore we had no knowledge of this recall until after the accident.  It has been determined that this trailer was not ever brought in during the recall for compliance.  It has also been determined by a Forensic Investigator for one of the Insurance companies that the cause of this accident was indeed improper welding of the rear tandems.    The West Virginia State Police were notified immediately.  The State Police, Handley Fire Department, JanCare Ambulance, Hutch's Body Shop, and HazMat teams responded immediately to the accident.  The HazMat teams used various methods of containing the acid, fuel, and debris from spreading further from the accident site.  A spill truck was brought in, spill pads, oil dry and soda were used in the clean-up of the accident scene.  A wrecker and roll-back truck towed the tractor and trailer away from the site.    At this time the cost to Shoun Trucking for the clean up and damage to the area of the accident are not able to be determined because of the various agencies involved have not yet processed the costs.  At the time of this writing the debris is still being transported to the Michigan Disposal Waste Treatment Plant.  The only costs that we are aware of in their entirity are that of the loss of cargo and the physical damage to our vehicles.
column169: When a recall takes place the factory should track the involved vehicles until that particular vehicle has complied with the recall.

column168: On Saturday 5/20/06 a "Walk-In" Client came in to ship 3 Boxes to Antigua.  She filled out all the appropriate paperwork and stated that she was shipping Necklaces.  Amerijet flies out of our Hub in Miami and upon loading the Dedicated Truck which transports our freight into the Hub,Leonard Harris,Warehose Agent,responsible for the truck loading Smelled something and Alerted his Supervisor,Lou Montella Jr.  Upon checking into the situation,Lou decided that the work area needed to be Evacuated and then he proceeded to contact the Port Authority Response Number who in turn asked him to contact the FDNY as Amerijet's Building is not on Port Authority Grounds.  Leonard was able to locate the Box which had a Visible Wet Spot,due to the Bottle Opening inside the Box.  The FDNY responded initially and shortly thereafter,Mr.Nicholas Healey,Special Agent, from the F.A.A. Hazmat Division was on the scene.  Mr.Healy proceeded to take Picturs and Notes and after his Inspection noted that the Material was a "Flammable Liquid/Acetone"....commonly known as Nail Polish Remover.  The Shipper of Record was called in to retrieve her Carton and spoke with Mr. Healey.  Please note,that in an effort to Minimize the lingering Smell,all Gates/Doors leading into the Facility were left Open,so that, Fresh Air could enter and this Helped quite a Bit.
column169: Amerijet has Posted Signs which were provided by the F.A.A. around our Facility and as a Compliment to these signs we are going to Verbally remind our shippers of the Need for Full Disclosure as well as beef up the Random Inspection of Packages entering Our Facility.

column168: This was a rollover accident.  We believe our employee, John Supon, went off the right shoulder and tried to correct the truck and in doing so the truck went to the left hand side of the road hitting the ditch and rolling over 2 and ½ times.   Our employee was ejected from the cab and was injured due to the crash, not the propane release.  The release was at the vapor return line where the valve goes into the tank.  Once the pressure was down on the tank our servicemen took the broken piece of the fitting out of the tank and installed a ¾ inch nipple and shut off valve to stop the leak of product.  The estimated time of release was from 12:20 PM to 5 PM.  It is estimated that approximately 20 gallons of vapor released.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "Slip off Stay off" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facs to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate.  Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers.  Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: Portable tank container was discovered with a strong odor (i.e. propane) odor eminating from it. The odor cound be noted around the midsection of the tank within a 15 ft. perimeter. column168: Richard Wulff, Mechanical Superintendent, reported Tankcar RCRX 1521 was releasing vapor and a mist from the top of the car. The car was on an industrial lead at Missouri Avenue in East St Louis, IL. John Miller, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified. Necessary state and federal regulatory notifications were made. At 01:13 PM, Miller reported a blind flange was less than tool tight. The bolts on the flange were secured, and the vapor subsided.

The driver arrived on site, met with a plant employee who checked his paperwork and connection and then signed his paperwork to indicate he was properly hooked up, the product was correct, and the tank(s) had adequate capacity. The first 80% of the delivery was unremarkable. The product flowed as expected with no leakage or spillage.  Without warning, at about 11:45 a.m. on Monday 05/08/06, the flexible hose transferring the acid was propelled from its place at the rear of the tank trailer along with the 4 bolt-flange to which it was connected. The driver was blocked from reaching the nearest (rear) internal valve shut-off lever, so he shouted a warning to those plant personnel in the general area, ran to the front fender, and closed the internal valve using the emergency shut-off lever mounted on the front fender. The time this took was slight, but approximately 30 gallons of Hydrochloric acid spilled onto the immediate area of the plant. Some flowed onto concrete, some went down an acid containment grate built for that purpose, and some went onto a dirt area.  To mitigate the effects of the release, bags of soda ash, already on site for use in case of a spill, were dispersed over the area wet with acid. This step was taken by Appalachian Well Services plant employees to neutralize the Hydrochloric acid at least partially. Appalachian Well Services Safety Director, Joe Machado, was able to use materials on hand to allow movement of the remaining approximately 1000 gallons from the cargo tank to the plant storage tank.  This author quickly notified Great West Casualty Company (GWCC) after learning of the spill event. They arranged for Rick Nehrig, Independent Adjuster, of J.F. Terry Associates to travel to the site and coordinate any needed clean up effort. He estimated 30 gallons of Hydrochloric acid spilled in front of the storage tanks. The contaminated area was in an “L” shape — with the dirt affected about 39’ long and up to 8’ wide, and 37’ of cement affected. Some acid traveled over a grate and down a drain to an area designed to contain acid in such a situation.  Mr. Nebrig’s home office worked with the Debbie Brzoska at the GWCC office, and agreed to hire HM}ITTC, operating out of Carlisle, PA, to complete the clean-up operation. When the skies became cloudy and dark, Mr. Nebrig contacted the Elderton, PA Fire Department for containment assistance/advice. They involved the area Hazmaz Coordinator, who recommended tarping the area. Safety Director, Joe Machado, coordinated accessing the tarps, and getting them in place. It did not rain.   At 9:15 p.m., HMIITTC’s crew and equipment arrived on scene and began clean up of the contaminated soil. A back hoe owned by Appalachian Well Services was used, without charge, to collect the contaminated dirt. The crew dug 1/2 to 1 inch at some hot spots to collect a total of 4 barrels of contamination. Then they tested the remaining soil. Results were all within the 6 to 7 pH range, reportedly consider
column169: The failed CPVC Schedule 80 nipple was saved and returned to the terminal along with the rest of the piping. The First Class Transport (FCT) Maintenance Supervisor, an experienced Tank Mechanic under contract to FCT, the FCT driver who made the delivery and the FCT Safety Director, looked over the parts closely. It appeared that the CPVC Schedule 80 material split cleanly across its width, as though it had been cut by an axe. The driver was standing in the immediate area of the piping, and saw no leaking prior to the hose and flange shooting off Given that this trailer has only been in service since 3/31/06, we spent considerable time considering possible physical insults to the piece which may have weakened it. We could not identify that anything had been dropped on or near that area. We could not identify anybody who tripped over the hose or any other “shock” to the hose. All our drivers have known for several months (since we first began using FRP Trailers) that the hoses must be disconnected at the 4- bolt flange before travel to prevent damage to the CPVC Schedule 80 plumbing from road vibration. We could find no evidence that this rule had been broken. The delivery was made under air pressure supplied by the tractor, but only a maximum of about 18 p.s.i. was being used, much less than would be expected to burst the nipple.   Having found no evidence of a physical insult to weaken the CPVC Schedule 80 nipple, we were left with the hypothesis that the material, while recommended by an FRP tank manufacturer, may not be able to stand up to some real-life highway and plant conditions. Alternately, the piece may have been defective, but we have no strong evidence to support this. The nipple is considered to be the weakest piece in the piping system based on thickness comparisons with other parts. The Maintenance Supervisor and mechanic arrived at a way to use a 3 to 2 Teflon encapsulated cast iron flange, a much sturdier part, to eliminate the nipple from the plumbing. Extra parts have been ordered to replace the nipple from other FRP tank trailers with similar plumbing setups. The driver assigned to pull a sister tanker to FCT-1572 was given a fill! report of the incident by the FCT driver present at Appalachian Well Systems. This will allow him to take special precautions during deliveries (where he and others stand during delivery, very carefully checking the plumbing prior to unloading) to keep everybody safe until all materials are available to re-do the plumbing.

column168: On May 22, 2006, at 1630 hours, Jim Briski, CSXT HazMat Manager, was notified of a release of Sulfuric Acid from tank car GATX 6650 located at the Wansford Yard in Evansville, IN. Switch Crew Y220-23 was making up a train for a local delivery when switchman S.D. Helms was sprayed with sulfuric acid from the top of GATX 6650. Mr. Helms received immediate care by neturalizing the affected area with water and there after transported to the hospital and treated for his exposure to the product. He was released from the hospital with no lost time (not FRA reportable). The car was isolated in track 002. Summit Environmental was contracted to inspect and clean GATX 6650. During inspection they discovered that the frangible rupture disc had ruptured. When removed for inspection, it was noted that the disc was stamped 100 lbs. A proper 165 lb.disc was installed. The car was then sprayed with a solution to neutralize the acid and afterwards released to destination for unloading. Chemtrec was notified (05222006044) and contact was made with the shipper. CSXT requested the shipper inspect all further cars before releasing for transportation. CSXT also inspected ten rail cars intransit on CSX at various locations for installation of the proper rupture disc. All cars inspected were equiped with a 165 lbs rupture disc.   NARRI: 2 (5+5+0) x (2+2) = 80   Cause code = 441 (Frangible disc ruptured)

column168: At 00:03 hrs.. on 05/18/2006, CSX Transportation discovered an active leak from the bottom of WACX 151215 in the CSXT Collier Yard. The car was hauling Phosphoric Acid, 65-80% Food grade material. CSX Transportation Haz-Mat dispatched Hepaco Environmental to respond to the incident. It was discovered that the leak was coming from an 8-bolt blind flange that was bolted to the bottom of the car. The blind flange was bolted to the area where a bottom outlet valve would be; 7 of 8 bolts were tool tight. One nut was tightened 1/2 a turn. The leak did not stop after tightening the last nut. An empty tank car was brought in to perform a transload of the material. After the transload was completed, the blind flange was removed. The blind flange gasket was defective causing the leak. The car was clean and purged by Hepaco and an FRA movement approval will be requested by PCS Sales prior to the car being moved to a repair shop.   Chemtrec # 0518200600   Cause Code: 641   NARRI: 5(5±3+0)x(4+0)=1 60

At approximately 9:15 on Friday May 19, 2006 the safety shower in the rail dock area was activated. Upon hearing the alarm, Marsulex employees headed to the rail dock area and found that a SUN rail car, containing spent sulfuric acid, was leaking spent acid onto the ground. The rail dock employee, Paul Mansfield, was found standing in the rail dock’s safety shower. Accounts of the incident from interviewing the employee indicate that the employee was trying to stay ahead of his work. In doing so, he indicates that he failed to carry-out a critical step in the process.  The employee states that he had hooked-up the eduction pipe to the SUN car to vent it down for unloading. This car was the southern most car in the loading/unloading area. After hooking-up the car to be vented down, the employee went to the north car to continue his work. After completing his routine work on the north car, he returned to the south car. The employee picked up an impact wrench to remove the eduction cap from the car. Upon removing the cap the employee realized that he had missed a critical step in the venting process. Once acid began flowing out of the eduction pipe the cap could not be reinstalled until flow stopped. Prior to removing the eduction cap the employee is required to ensure the car is not under pressure. The employee failed to verify this critical step.   As stated by the employee, as he started to remove the eduction cap he felt pressure on the pipe. Knowing he could not re-tighten the cap, he jumped back from the area. Given the car was still under pressure as the employee jumped back, letting go of the impact wrench, the car’s contents began to forcefully escape.   All required PPE was being worn at the time of the incident, however, the employee was sprayed with spent acid on the right side of the face, neck, and on his right forearm. The face and neck area were sprayed as the employee turned his head away from the flow of material. His right forearm was contacted due to the force of the material spraying up and under his rubber coat sleeve.  The employee stood in the rail dock emergency shower for 7 minutes. Then transferred, under his own control, to the shower in the employee locker room. He remained in this shower for another 20 minutes.  It is estimated that 4,000 pounds of material was spilled during this incident which lasted 2 minutes. At approximately 9:30 the NRC, SERC, and LEPC were contacted regarding the spill event. Paul Wilson and Tim Daniels from the Coast Guard were on-site at 12:10 pm for less than a half hour. The car wash down and the safety shower water caused material to migrate onto the BP refinery property. BP was advised of the incident and that spilled material was flowing onto their property. Material flowed onto an asphalt paved area. Marsulex called EQ Industrial Services to mitigate the spill on-site. Onyx was utilized by BP to clean-up the spent acid that had made its way onto their property.  The spent acid on the BP s

column168: June 21, 2006   Hazardous Materials Incident Report 2006061074   Lykins Transportation, Inc.   Date of Incident: 5/31/06   Location of Incident: 1290 E. Second Street, Covington, KY 41011   NRC Report # 799019   Re: Part VI— Description of Events & Package Pailure:   Part VII— Recommendations/Actions Taken To Prevent Recurrence:   VI— Description of Events & Package Failure: Driver/truck was dispatched to the Dugan & Meyers construction site to pump out 100 gallons of# 2 fuel oil that had been mis-delivered into the on-site (Dugan & Meyers) 500 gallon “unleaded gasoline” storage tank and the then deliver virgin unleaded gasoline back into the same “gasoline’ tank.   Driver had completed the pump out of the on-site storage tank; and removed all pump out hoses and pipes and stored them accordingly onto our tank wagon unit. Note: a a precaution to cross-contamination of the products the driver used the tank wagon fuel oil pump for the pump out activity and the gasoline pump for delivery activity. Upon completion of the pump out Driver then reconnected the fuel oil pump hose, on passenger side of our tank wagon and opened the jumper valve for the gasoline pump hose, which was connected onto compartment # 1 of the tank wagon. Driver then went to back of tank wagon and pulled the gasoline delivery hose over to the customers on-site tank. Driver then returned to the rear of the tank wagon and reached in and pulled the clutch disengage lever and engaged the PTO switch. Upon releasing the lever, the driver states he heard the tank wagon pump engage and then heard the sound of liquid hitting the street. Driver immediately checked the passenger side of the tank wagon to see if the jumper ]ose was connected properly and then noticed gasoline flowing from underneath the tank wagon and down onto unloading area ground and subordinate to adjacent roadway. Driver then ran back to the controls to disengage the pump and close the safety valve. According to the driver, by this time the tank wagon engine had began to run out of control — presumably from the engine picking up the gasoline fumes from the escaping product. Driver states that at about the time he pulled the lever is when an explosion occurred; knocking him approximately twenty-five (25) feet away from truck, Driver theiru got up onto his feet to get away and went about another fifty (50) feet and fell down to the pavement. Driver states he then got back up and was moving farther away from the scene. Driver realized that the personnel of Dugan & Meyers had called 911 fo:r emergency response and our driver effected call to our dispatch office and notified company of the incident. Driver as subsequently removed from the scene to a nearby hospital and treated and released for minor injuries. Response to the scene involved the Covington, KY fire and police departments, Cincinnati, Oh fire department, Kenton County Emergency Management Agency, Kentucky EPA, Homeland Security and FBI representatives. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT AND SECURED SCENE. FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED LIQUID PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE AGRILIANCE TRAILER. AFTER FURTHER ASSESSMENT OF SHIPPING DOCUMENTS AND CONFERRING WITH THE AGRILIANCE REPRESENTATIVE ON THE SCENE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER WAS ZINC 20% COMPLEX NULEX (BRAND NAME). ONCE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED, A HAZMAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED FROM GREAT BEND, KANSAS.   THE TOP OF THE 275 GALLON IBC RUPTURED, WHICH ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS. THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT APPROXIMATELY 175 GALLONS, REMAINED IN THE IBC TO BE RECOVERED LATER IN THE CLEANUP PHASE OF THE INCIDENT. PRODUCT RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT SPILLED ONTO THE HARD SURFACE OF THE HIGHWAY AND TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 75 FEET ALONG THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, AND INTO THE DITCH ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY. SPILLED LIQUID MATERIAL COVERED APPROXIMATELY 750 SQUARE FEET. THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS CONTAINED BY CONSTRUCTING A DIKE AROUND THE AFFECTED AREA. BROOMS AND A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF WATER WERE USED TO REMOVED THE PRODUCT RESIDUE FROM THE ROAD'S HARD SURFACE. RUNOFF WAS CONFINED WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THE SUDDEN AND DRAMATIC SHIFTING OF PACKAGES DURING THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT CAUSED THE IBC TO FAIL. THE INITIAL RESPONSE AND CLEANUP TOOK APPROXIMATELY 7.5 HOURS. REMOVAL OF THE CONTAMINATED ROCK AND SOIL OCCURRED ON MAY 30 AND LASTED APPROXIMATELY 7 HOURS.
column169: FOLLOW UP ACTIVITIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT INCLUDED ADDITIONAL SAFETY TRAINING FOR DRIVERS AND EMPLOYEES.

column168: On the morning of 5/25/2006 a driver for CTL Distribution, Inc was dispatched to deliver a load of chlorine to Ullrich Water Treatment Plant in Austin, TX. The driver arrived at the terminal facility at approximately 3:00 am and performed the appropriate inspection of the pre-loaded chlorine trailer. The chlorine trailer was pre-loaded on 5/24/2006 by Altivia Corporation. After completing the appropriate inspections the driver left the Altivia Corporation facility in Houston, TX en-route to Ulirich Water Treatment Plant in Austin, TX. The driver did not experience any problems while en-route until he was approximately 6 miles east of 1-35 in Austin, TX. The driver had approached an intersection that has a traffic control devices. The light was red; the driver came to a controlled stop at the traffic light. When the light turned green the driver proceeded through the intersection in a westerly direction. The driver cleared the intersection and was approaching the next intersection at Springdale, when the light turned green the driver was approximately traveling about 25-30 mph when he looked into his mirrors and noticed a yellowish green vapor coming from the top rear of the trailer. The driver immediately pulled his unit to the right hand shoulder of Highway 290 and positioned the unit completely off the travel portion of the highway and secured the vehicle. The driver immediately exited the cab of the tractor and called 911 to report the incident. After calling 911 the driver immediately notified CTL Distribution, Inc. along with Altivia Corporation to report the incident. Steven White from Altivia Corporation the shipper and owner of the trailer notified SRS a contracted Environmental Response Service. SRS had personnel at the Ullrich Water Treatment Plant in Austin, TX, as SRS was Dontracted by Altivia Corporation to unload the bulk chlorine trailer when it arrived at the plant facility.  Altivia Corporation hired Specialized Response Solution (SRS) to manage and coordinate the transfer of the chlorine and clean up. Altivia Corporation also hired the Center for Toxicology and Environmental Health to conduct air monitoring around the perimeter of the trailer. Altivia Corporation hired Steven Emerson, PHD of Emerson Technical Analysis to perform a root cause analysis of the incident.  It has been determined that the reason the pressure relief valve opened was due to contaminates inside the trailer (i.e. water). The trailer involved in this incident had just received the required inspection and a procedure to dry the inside of the trailer was required. A third party (Brite Clean) was hired by Altivia Corporation to perform the required dry procedures prior to Altivia Corporation loading the trailer. Brite Clean was in possession of the trailer prior to loading by Altivia Corporation.  After the initial release occurred the area around the unit was isolated and the highway was closed and the resident where given instruction for shelter in place. T
column169: It would appear that drying procedures at the facility (Brite Clean) that Altivia Corporation hired failed to monitor moisture content. There are monitoring devices that monitor dew point and this should be part of the drying procedures to monitor the moisture to verify that the inside of the trailer is completely dry.  I have attached a letter sent by Steven White General Manager for Altivia Corporation to the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality.  If you need any additional information please contact me at 800-237-9088 ext. E3188.

Greg Jacobs, Yardmaster, reported a small amount of product had released from Tankcar GATX 52902 which was located in Yard Six, Track 703, of the Fourth Street Yard in Los Angeles, CA. Mr. Jacobs advised the release had come from the top of the tankcar but did not reach the side of the tankcar, nor did any product reach the ground. Duffy Exon, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. Mr. Exon requested the Los Angeles Fire Department be notified and respond for assistance. At 11:28 AM, Ramiro Barba, Senior Manager of Terminal Operations, requested to speak with Duffy Exon, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, due to the Los Angeles Fire Departments request to shut down train traffic and evacuate a large area of the Fourth Street Yard and surrounding businesses. Exon was contacted and a conference call was established. Mr. Barba stated Ventura Foods was the only business other than Union Pacific employees, that had been evacuated.Update: Robert Bavier Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety advised that the cause of the release was a missing manway gasket. The gasket was replaced and the car was released.

column168: TANKCAR UTLX 645057, WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP AT MILE POST 902.00 OF THE PHOENIX SUBDIVISION (CAMPOYARD) IN PHOENIX AZ. MR. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED. MR. JACKSON NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE INCORPORATED, EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. ERI DISCOVERED THE CAR HAD RELEASED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY COVER AND THAT IT HAD EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE PLUG AND VAPOR LINE PLUG WERE ALSO LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. AFTER THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND DETERMINED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION, ERI SECURED ALL EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS TO TOOL TIGHT CONDITION. BOTH THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINE PLUGS WERE TIGHTENED AND SECURED. THE CAR WAS INSPECTED AND NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE FOUND. MR. JACKSON RELEASED THE CAR TO DESTINATION AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.
